featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-Abtran-RVW27529923.htm', 'id': 27529923, 'currentJob': False, 'reviewDateTime': '2019-06-21 03:19:39.833', 'jobTitle': 'Customer Support', 'location': '', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'Customer Support', 'headline': "Don't work here for more than 1 year", 'pros': 'I started as my area of work is not in demand and I  believe it is important to work. Therefore the benefit was employment in itself. 
Learnt about the area I was working in with insider knowledge now which is helpful
I am Degree educated and previously worked in professional jobs
On a positive note - i was going for an other job and they noted I had lasted more than 2 years in Abtran during the recession. They stated it showed determination of character and a great work ethic. The issue with Abtran is that if you stay  longer than a year - its hard to get a reference as your old company will be no longer valid and Abtran give standard reference stating only the time you worked there. 
Is it better than the dole? its a tricky one - while working allows your stamps to be paid and sometimes there are courses at Abtran - the issue is the bullying will damage your self esteem and you are less likely to be able to get a new job.
Parking is good
Canteen: Available - food not great. Have to pay for tea/coffee
Toilets: Reasonably clean
Pros: Its actually really hard to be fired and they normally take any one who applies for a job.', 'cons': 'Pay - minimum. About 19, 000
Any time I worked overtime for time and half there was always an issue with the pay. Always a debate stating no we never agreed time and a half. 
Schedule: No flexibility - requested half a day off to collect my mum from hospital as she was having a body part removed. I was refused. Never had called in sick, very professional at all time. 
Behaviour - very poor from other staff and management.
Bullying is the default setting with this company - the way they deal with staff is called command and control. They aim to control you - demean and put you down.
I found this extremely difficult as previously having worked  as a professional in a professional environment I was unused to this. 
Also I was unused to this in my personal life as well. A lot of people who work here did not go to college, or a non technical course. If you are polite and well educated this really is not the company for you . - it will damage you. It is no disrespect to the people who work there - but if you are degree educated you will not have much in common. It is a starter job with a very young work force. People do not know who to include people in teams, make people fee welcome.
The management often are quite young and unprofessional. This is their first time dealing with people and all the mistakes are being made. Couple this with very high targets and for the most part a demotivated work force leads to an massively toxic environment. 
If this is your first job you may think this is the way people behave at work. You may think you need to cc  to a number of people - any error and highlight and blame . This is the case for Abran but in most other companies this behaviour is terrible and not appropriate.  
Pension: No
Benefits: No
Holidays: huge issue, very difficult to get holiday. You will miss weddings and if you think just because its a family wedding! you will be sadly mistaken.  
However is a manager likes a member of staff they will be given holidays.
The worst is if you have a seriously ill family member - there will be no flexibility', 'overall': 1, 'overallNumeric': 1}
name: Abtran

featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-Demonware-RVW9516061.htm', 'id': 9516061, 'currentJob': False, 'reviewDateTime': '2016-02-09 20:29:28.05', 'jobTitle': 'Employee', 'location': '', 'headline': 'Agree with the other reviewers', 'pros': '- Free lunch and snacks
- Free gym
- Internship pay is competitive. The pay is average if not slightly above market.
- Discounts on company games
- 35 hour work weeks until release time
- Lots of vacation days for full-timers
- Fun company events
- Good benefits for full-timers', 'cons': "Like others said, if you're under a good team, then I think you will really enjoy your time there. But for how small of a company, even the team to team experience can be quite different and some teams are very poorly run. 

- Management is juvenile and leadership is lacking. Because it grew so fast during a short period of time, I felt some managers that got promoted up are quite inexperienced and has no idea how to manage subordinates. 
- Cross team communication is non-existent. Leading to wasted time and effort. My team also lacked communication because my manager did not believe in meetings.
- Lack of career growth depending on your role. Never once had 1-on-1 time with my direct manager to discuss goals and expectations. No performance reviews of any type.
- Lack of opportunity to receive and give feedback. Hard to grow my career or improve the company when there is no way to give feedback. While no companies are ever perfect, the biggest red flag is that management never recognizes there is a problem.
- Interns are not used as potential for future hiring and might not be given interesting work to do. Don't expect any mentorship. As interns, we were told to not answer questions because it would bother full-timers. If you fail to execute a task, you would be treated as being incompetent. For these reasons, I would not recommend any interns to intern here. 
- Always sitting in the grey area of HR violations. (HR didn't do much while I was there) Be prepared that there might be borderline sexual comments directed at people.", 'overall': 2, 'overallNumeric': 2}
name: Demonware

featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-NextRoll-RVW30130728.htm', 'id': 30130728, 'currentJob': True, 'reviewDateTime': '2019-10-31 15:31:58.673', 'jobTitle': 'N/A', 'location': 'San Francisco, CA', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'N/A', 'headline': 'Amazing Culture, Innovative Teams, Work Life Balence', 'pros': "- This culture is second to none. I've never worked at a company where your coworkers become like family. This extends to former employees who still stop by and say hi to everyone at the office
- Smart People- everyone who works here are hard workers, with a lot of wisdom and industry knowledge to learn from. I would think after 2 years I would be bored and want to find a new challenge, but this is not the case. I learn something new from management/coworkers almost every day
- Work Life Balance - I've never worked at a company where most employees actually take a lunch break, and nobody gives you a hard time for taking time off to spend with family

featuredReview: {'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-Apple-Growth-Partners-RVW29010224.htm', 'id': 29010224, 'currentJob': False, 'reviewDateTime': '2019-09-03 17:19:07.243', 'jobTitle': 'Manager', 'location': 'Akron, OH', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'Manager', 'headline': 'Good Company to start a career at and work for', 'pros': 'Good company, very giving in the sense that they do more than simply encourage employees to learn and grow in their careers, they actively support it. For new accountants, this is a good place to get started in your career. For experienced accountants, it is a great place to continue your career.  Their "core hours" policy and ample paid time off is a huge plus, and for the most part there is little micro-management. I enjoyed working at the firm.', 'cons': "The culture between different offices can be shocking considering the offices are all within a 20 minute drive of each other, as is the prevalence of different social cliques within each office.  The benefits package could be improved, but the company does kick in a good amount, and there are some benefits they provide that just don't exist at other places. Considering the number of families and family-friendly benefits they offer, I found it difficult to understand why the company couldn't do better for family health coverage, or at least give an honest effort to shopping around.  The tendency to rely on outside consultants really undermines the true potential of the leadership to take the firm to the next level. At times, it's like working in a real-life management book of the month club. Operations side is severely overworked while the accounting staff is babied.", 'overall': 4, 'overallNumeric': 4}
name: Apple Growth Partners

featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-ARM-Group-Inc-RVW24237507.htm', 'id': 24237507, 'currentJob': False, 'reviewDateTime': '2019-01-16 09:22:37.557', 'jobTitle': 'Staff Geologist', 'location': 'Columbia, MD', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'Staff Geologist', 'headline': 'Great people in a supportive environment', 'pros': "My supervisor was up front and honest during the interview about what I could expect, and everything turned out to be true. I had a great working relationship with both my supervisor and coworkers, and never felt out of line going to them with an issue or question, no matter how seemingly insignificant. I immediately got plugged into their largest project and my involvement was gradually escalated. I learned more in my ten months there than in my entire tenure at my previous position. 

Management will let you when you've made a mistake, but you're treated like a human being in the process and given excellent constructive feedback. Very friendly and laid back atmosphere, I felt like I could go out for a beer with any of my co workers.

Superb benefit pricing, only $80 a month for healthcare, dental, and vision. I only ever used the vision benefit and I had zero issues at my doctor's office.", 'cons': "Compensation is a bit lower than at larger firms, which ultimately was the breaking point for me given the very high cost of living in the Baltimore area. That being said, when I approached management with the offer for my current role, they made every effort to try to find more work to get my compensation closer to what I'd been offered, so they certainly demonstrated loyalty in that regard. 

There was lots of emphasis on one project in particular which made things somewhat mundane at times. But I was plugged into other projects from time to time when opportunities came up. This was definitely the exception though, as the vast majority of everyone's attention was focused on this one project. This isn't necessarily a bad thing, as its a massive client, but it resulted in repetition at times.

It can also be tough to find billable work in the office when the field work is slow. This is pretty typical in consulting from what I understand, and  definitely isn't unique to ARM.", 'overall': 5, 'overallNumeric': 5}
name: ARM Group Inc

featuredReview: {'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-Atos-Medical-RVW28482334.htm', 'id': 28482334, 'currentJob': False, 'reviewDateTime': '2019-08-06 23:30:24.73', 'jobTitle': 'Customer Support Representative', 'location': '', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'Customer Support Representative', 'headline': 'Loved the job - but not enough to stay and burn out', 'pros': 'When done right, this was (and still could be) an amazing place to work. When I first started with the company, the patients were always first priority with the saying “No Laryngectomy Left Behind”. It was truly humbling working with these people who endured such a life changing surgery. I ended up with an amazing territory, a phenomenal RSM and TSM, the sweetest patients you could ask for, and hospitals that made it known that they trusted you to do what was best for their people. When I say I loved my job, I truly loved it. Inside the office you had some of the kindest co-workers who (usually) had a great since of humor. Again, when I started, employees were actually enjoying being at their job and would frequently get large groups together after work. Unfortunately as tensions became higher from frustrations and miscommunications in the work place, that passion once found in this company began slowly burning out - and so did the employees. I sincerely hope that things either have changed or start changing soon because, like I mentioned earlier, Atos could still be an amazing company and family to be a part of.', 'cons': 'I am honestly very saddened to read the reviews recently posted because I believe once management is able to acknowledge there are problems that need to be addressed, they could still turn company morale around. It is well understood the company is growing at a very fast pace by everyone there, but because of that you have to learn to delegate tasks and get more organized in your processes. Every single person at that company has so many tasks on their plate that should not be their responsibility (even management… one person cannot manage three departments effectively). With the growth of the company came a lot of changes and a huge lack of communication between everyone in the company. It’s a daily question as to what the policy is for everything on any given day which makes it very difficult to confidently do your job. Asking a neighbor usually doesn’t help because they aren’t confident either. Then when you finally locate a manager after they have been pulled into meetings all day, they say they will “get back to you”. Usually they don’t get back to you unless you repeatedly remind them of it (again since they have so many other things on their plate as well). But typically that’s because they also are not being told what to do by higher ups. There is such a lack of flow and consistency, as well as a lack of communication, which is the perfect recipe for the chaos Atos is experiencing internally.', 'overall': 3, 'overallNumeric': 3}
name: Atos Medical

featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-Axonista-RVW12079274.htm', 'id': 12079274, 'currentJob': False, 'reviewDateTime': '2016-09-26 13:25:09.157', 'jobTitle': 'Employee', 'location': '', 'headline': 'Wish I never took the job offer', 'pros': 'Freedom to experiment in your own time', 'cons': 'One of the major issues within Axonista is the huge lack of communication between management and employees. They claim to be a start up but completely lack the mentality. Daily stand up never happened during my time here and you’ll be pulled from every side to work on whatever management feel is important to them at the time (leading to incomplete work and wasting time).

Management want to have complete control over everything within the company and due to this they are constantly juggling things from every department and unwilling to let other employees make informed decisions.

The employee break room is non existent due to it being occupied on a daily basis for unimportant reasons. Its guaranteed you won’t be socialising with any other employees and you’ll be eating your lunch at your desk.

Due to this lack of culture there is a depressing office atmosphere as barely any employees speak to each other. There’s a sense of relief when management are not in the office as you will feel they’re watching your every move and ready to discipline if even one minute late.

Bickering between management within the office (and even during meetings) caused unease and led to an unfavourable atmosphere in the office.

Arrogant management will belittle you and other employees on a daily basis with either sly remarks or critiquing your work as if you have no integrity. Instances where employees have been spoken to in such a disgusting manner makes me question why I didn’t quit sooner.

I wish someone would have informed of all these downfalls before I joined.', 'overall': 1, 'overallNumeric': 1}
name: Axonista

name: John Fluevog Boots & Shoes

featuredReview: {'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-BSI-America-RVW29080536.htm', 'id': 29080536, 'currentJob': True, 'reviewDateTime': '2019-09-06 20:52:44.313', 'jobTitle': 'Assessor', 'location': 'Atlanta, GA', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'Assessor', 'headline': 'Present Day REVIEW', 'pros': "So far, I found the hiring and management department for the Medical Device team to be very honest.  I did not feel they were just looking for a body.  They were honest about the amount of travel.  Acknowledged my concerns about some of the job review complaints I've researched. And they shared with me the processes that are now in place to address some of those concerns.  The desire to identify, acknowledge and improve is to me a good sign. I joined right when these changes were taking place and felt an honest present-day review was needed.  Majority of the team members and fellow assessors have been great to work with. Then you also have a few outliers in the bunch. Each assessor comes with their own wealth of knowledge on whatever past industry they worked in before BSI and we all teach each other. Travel expenses are treated with a fast turn around time.  Being apart of a big organization, the benefits are good and 4 weeks of PTO are a plus.  Working remote, communication can be challenging, but I think all remote jobs share this.  So far my manager, planners, payroll and the HR department does a good job communicating back in a reasonable time.  The entire management team is new.  Note:  They are made up of previous assessors who have been promoted from within the organization to these postions.  So far my manager has been very encouraging and showed care and concern for my wellbeing during training and during a personal hardship. Other management members have reached out to offer themselves as additional resources.  Learning resources are abundant, you just have to be resourceful enough to communicate your needs.  Traveling is extensive but the pro is that the organization acknowledges this and they are mass hiring to help alleviate this.  Ownership of travel points collected from expense s is nice.  Paid certifications and classes is a pro.  And finally the most important pro, no one micromanaging your everyday work activities as long as you do what needs to get done and do it right!", 'cons': "Training structure - not detailed enough for the needs of new assessors.  But from what I've heard and seen from individuals hired after my group, it's improving.  There are too many different learning modules and sign in's to keep up with.  Communication lacks some sort of control process.  I have found that either I or other fellow assessors have been left out of important email communications. IT turn around request can be a little long.", 'overall': 5, 'overallNumeric': 5}
name: BSI America

featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-CLUB-CLIO-RVW7391898.htm', 'id': 7391898, 'currentJob': False, 'reviewDateTime': '2015-07-29 08:37:03.097', 'jobTitle': 'Retail Sales Associate', 'location': 'New York, NY', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'Retail Sales Associate', 'headline': "Worst job experience I've EVER had", 'pros': 'You get a 40% off discount on everything, which is the only way I can justify purchasing a lipstick that they sell for $20.', 'cons': 'Where do I begin...

1. I had to call THEM to find out if I was hired. I called on a Friday, when I had been interviewed 8 days previously, and when I called she said she already put me on the schedule. Um, THANKS FOR THE HEADS UP! Then she said she'd email me my schedule within the hour, and 7 hours later I finally receive the email. I was already thrown off by this point.
2. There is no fridge or microwave in the break room. So basically, if you work there you have to buy a lunch during your shift or figure out how to bring a substantial lunch that doesn't have to be kept cold or heated up. 
3. There are no lockers to keep your belongings in. Call me paranoid, but I counted my cash before and after my shift to make sure none was missing. 
4. I was not even given an orientation. Isn't that what all businesses do with new hires? You know, go over paperwork and all of the important details of working with them??
5. Even though this is not a commission based company, you are not allowed to team up with a coworker to upsell the products. I was scolded twice for helping out and giving my two cents to a customer that my former coworker already helped/was helping. Ridiculously competitive for absolutely NO reason. 
6. If you are not Korean or if you don't speak Korean, expect to get singled out and feel like an outcast. Even though it's a small store, my coworkers never took the time to make me feel welcomed. They always spoke Korean to each other and I could never join in on their conversation, and the managers all speak Korean to each other. I've never felt so singled out at any other job I've ever had. 
7. On my last day, my former coworkers could not have made it more clear that they didn't want me there. I got attitude from two out of the three girls there and I would bet anything that they told the third girl not to speak to me. I got the worst attitude from one of them when I tried helping out with a customer. She acted as if I insulted her ancestors and cursed her family, when all I did was try to help and learn by interacting with the customer. She did not even approach me in a professional manner, all I got was a horrible confrontation. 
8. Their break system makes ABSOLUTELY NO SENSE. Basically, if you come to work in the morning, you get an hour for a break (which is more time than I got at any other job, so you're giving up a whole hour's worth of pay). If you come in after 12pm, you get no break. That's right, NO BREAK, yet if you work in the morning, you get a whole hour. What am I told about that? "That's the Korean way". Last time I remembered, we are still in the United States. My former manager said you're supposed to eat lunch before you come in. It took me an hour and a half by bus and train to get there. I eat breakfast at 9:30AM and leave by 11 ish, and get there around 12:30. My shifts always started at 1PM and ended at 8PM, so if I had not gotten a break, I would not be eating again until 12 hours later at 9:30PM. At every other job I've worked at, even if I only worked 4 hours, I got a break. if I worked more than 4 hours, I got a 30. So I did not take no for an answer, and because of that I was given a break. If I were in any other job and I worked 1-8, I would get a non-paid 30, and then a paid 15. In my opinion, I'd rather do that then lose a whole hour off my paycheck. 

On my first day, I wore my hair in a half up bun, with the rest down. There were 3 managers and 3 coworkers there with me that day and no one told me I had to wear my hair up. On my fourth and last day (no manager was there) I wore it the same way, and was told as soon as I walked in that I had to put my hair up. So I said no, this is the kind of thing I should have been told on my first day, and that the next time I come in, I will have my hair up. Their reasoning was "Well your first day was supposed to be easy". I don't come to work to be babied, I come to work to WORK. Every day I would learn something that would contradict what someone else told me, or something that should have been covered in an, oh I don't know, an ORIENTATION?? 

Two out of the four days I was there, I was not taught a single thing. I stood there or cleaned the makeup, that was it. And the manager's excuse was that she wasn't there a few days. I'll also make it clear that she is not the only manager, and that there are people there who could have trained me. I told her that there should have been a schedule of training for me that could have been followed even when she was not there. There was absolutely no challenge and I could not see myself growing professionally by working there. 

After the horrible confrontation by my former coworker on my fourth day, I wasn't taking it anymore. After standing and doing nothing for 5 hours, I grabbed my things and walked out an hour and a half early. I have always given a two week notice to places I was leaving, but this time I had to look out for myself and my well being. 

Overall, this store is unwelcoming, unorganized, and unprofessional. I only worked at the store in New York City so I cannot speak for the other locations in NY and NJ, although I can imagine they aren't very different. 

If you want to be positively challenged, grow professionally, and most importantly, respected and treated well by your coworkers, don't work here.', 'overall': 1, 'overallNumeric': 1}
name: CLUB CLIO

We hire experienced, high performing, no non-sense inside sales employees that are highly motivated to move onto the next role.  

Inside sales leadership has taken a strong stance to promote sales development team members from within for our inside sales closing role. featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-Communicorp-GA-RVW17151673.htm', 'id': 17151673, 'currentJob': False, 'reviewDateTime': '2017-10-03 15:28:48.323', 'jobTitle': 'Employee', 'location': 'Columbus, GA', 'headline': 'A fine place if you put your head down, meet deadlines, and stay out of politics', 'pros': '- A ton of employee perks because this company is under Aflac. A lot of company get togethers, including the big Employee Appreciation.
- Most non-managers are extremely friendly, mainly because the company treats employees well. 
- Regular raises and bonuses if you do your job properly.', 'cons': "- Middle management is in a constant tug of war with each other. Meetings often exist to pass work around to other departments instead of collaborating to find solutions.
- Very high sales turnover, especially among new sales people. Unsure if that's because it's difficult to find new sales leads or if salespeople were poor. The environment was unsettling at times as there are 4 or 5 true cash cows that have to be kept happy or they'll threaten to leave.
- Workload can be a pain, especially depending on where you are in the pipeline. Certain departments get to push things through faster depending on who they talk to.
- Some managers have been with company for decades and aren't always the best at hiding old animosity with other managers.
- Opportunities for advancement may be limited, as most hold tightly to top positions.
- Your best chance to get hired is to know someone who already works there. At least half the new people I saw hired during my time knew someone at the company beforehand. 
- Technology can be lacking, especially in IT.", 'overall': 3, 'overallNumeric': 3}
name: Communicorp (GA)

featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-CGS-Health-RVW23487077.htm', 'id': 23487077, 'currentJob': False, 'reviewDateTime': '2018-11-19 15:45:06.33', 'jobTitle': 'Employee', 'location': '', 'headline': 'lying businessmen', 'pros': 'the interview was easy', 'cons': 'lie #1: i was lied to in the title negotiation when i was offered the position. i was told i could not have the word "manager" in my title because i wouldn't have direct reports, but after starting the position i learned that two people on the team were managers without direct reports. lie #2: the job itself / day-to-day was nothing like was described. after losing two clients there was nothing left for the team to do except pray for more clients to sign on & pray that current clients didn't choose another third party provider. lie #3: in the initial phone interview i was told health insurance was covered in full. in the in-person interview i was told insurance was covered at 80%. the latter ended up being true. 

also, the office has had a roach infestation, which was not entirely under control while i was there. management did not consider one roach by the bathroom to be a problem because it was not by the desk area, but the distance between the two was only a few feet.

the top person in charge has a tendency to be late to most meetings, including those with clients.

the office space is loud because people play their radio and/or socialize + part of the room is a call center. the office culture felt like lying businessmen trying to be less fratty by hiring females to get the office work done for them.', 'overall': 1, 'overallNumeric': 1}
name: CGS Health

featuredReview: {'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-CVS-Health-RVW5534098.htm', 'id': 5534098, 'currentJob': False, 'reviewDateTime': '2014-12-13 12:10:14.247', 'jobTitle': 'Store Manager', 'location': 'Orlando, FL', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'Store Manager', 'headline': '15 year manager', 'pros': 'I learned a lot working there as far as how to run a business as well as how to develop a team.  I had one of the most successful teams in the company ranking as the top store year over year in two separate markets, one in the Northeast one in the Southeast. I was a paragon winner with the company as well. My most recent DM was very supportive. I genuinely thank them for the opportunity and the knowledge that I acquired while working with them.', 'cons': 'Work hours were excessive. To be successful hours worked were borderline slavery. While I willingly worked them to be successful, the week you didn\'t you were immediately behind. Vacations were almost non existent due to constant visitors from corporate stopping in to do reviews. Holiday weeks were paid 4 days regular 1 holiday and you worked all 5. The facade of the stores looking great when these people stop by versus the reality of the business is polarizing. There were always teams of people and excessive expenditures of payroll thrown into stores prior to their visits. While I understood the need to make an appearance, it was always will always be a backwards way off thinking. Company preaches quality of life for their clients while quality of life for their employees is non-existent. As a "manager" in your average store you will be "managing" a total of one person during your shift, with a total of 10 people at location.  Location open hours will exceed total payroll hours ie Sun-Sat 7am-10pm = 15hrs per day x 7 days x 2 people = 210 hrs which excludes the need to have a person unload deliveries that come in during non opened hours. Your budgeted hours will be approximately 208 hrs. I will only mention that during the month of December that there are extended hours for the stores but no budgeted hours to accommodate. Stores are held to strict shrink targets with little to no control over external theft. Remember 2 people at location, if four people enter to steal there is nothing you can do to stop them. These are facts not personal prejudices.', 'overall': 5, 'overallNumeric': 5}
name: CVS Health

featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-Deloitte-RVW4712873.htm', 'id': 4712873, 'currentJob': False, 'reviewDateTime': '2014-08-04 09:56:03.507', 'jobTitle': 'AMS Associate', 'location': 'Boston, MA', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'AMS Associate', 'headline': 'Great Place to start your career - Carefully read the cons', 'pros': "These folks know exactly what they are doing. They set high standards, and consistently deliver. 
Their project expectations and planning is excellent. The top level management folks are extremely smart and have a great sense of vision and planning. If you go to company social events (which are very frequent by the way), it is quite easy to have conversations with upper management people (Partners). 

Deloitte's hiring pattern is very consistent. For the young starters, they hire smart, well spoken, and subtly aggressive candidates. They have excellent training and knowledge management. They have a well oiled and empowered HR and Tech Support group. Things get done pretty fast. 

Their paid time off program is really great, and pretty straight forward. No messing about.

They have a big social responsibility program that encourages volunteering. It also presents a great opportunity for youngsters to take event organizing responsibilities. This can be very very useful. Once, I volunteered for an event where we painted rooms for an orphanage center. There was a young guy who did the organizing. We were 10-12 people, with 3 senior executives actually doing paintwork. Quite unique. 


I have personally seen that Deloitte's top talents tend to start young, spend a 3-4 years, then take a hiatus to pursue a Graduate Degree (typically an MBA). The firm sometimes re-hires these consultants after their MBA with generous financial incentives. They offer much better packages to folks graduating from top universities. Sometimes they can offer huge joining bonuses. 

I worked in the IT consulting division.They tend to get top-end projects. On projects, the average age seems pretty low.  A lot of 20-somethings, then there are a handful of 30-40 year old people and some senior Management folks.

Beginner salaries can be a bit low. (which is expected. It takes some time to build credibility in the Consulting business)

Overall, a great place to start your professional career. If you pay attention, you will get seasoned very quickly.", 'cons': 'Work-life balance can become poor, especially during tight project timelines (This is expected in the Consulting Business). The employees have a significant amount of "firm-internal" training and knowledge contribution tasks. There are annual goal expectations. It can get tedious if you continuously work on high demand projects.

There is intense competition, especially during targeted promotion/milestone years. There can be some backstabbing. It's part of the experience. It is not as bad as it sounds, and seems manageable. 

A lot of times, being young and inexperienced has it's flaws. The company has a simple way of seasoning consultants. They get pushed into high pressure situations, and they learn fast, and quickly start managing their own work. But they tend to be blind towards intricate details, especially in complicated IT product implementations. This has an interesting effect. If someone is able to do the hands-on work, everyone else tries to piggy-back on that person for their actual work. The hands-on guy gets overwhelmed, and others try to use him/her as a key resource. 
-- I personally went through a crunch project, and found a number of people "managing expectations" (piggy backing), while a handful of people actually knew the end-to-end solution and did the hands-on work. 
This created a lot more work and mental anguish than needed. Because of the expressed pressure, the hands-on guys have a hard time building and growing their reputation and subsequent performance evaluation rating. This also affects the project execution timelines.

IMPORTANT: Make sure you thoroughly read through your employment agreement and understand the implications. In recent years, they have started hiring for specific projects ONLY. This falls under a particular "AMS service line". In this case, if your assigned project gets into a problem, you are exposed to the risk of employment termination. 
Their HR and Management are very helpful, and they will try to get you a new project. But there are several constraints like location, your skills, and limited time. I went through this, and it was somewhat unnerving. This was one of the reasons I ended up leaving the company.', 'overall': 5, 'overallNumeric': 5}
name: Deloitte

featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-Demonware-RVW9516061.htm', 'id': 9516061, 'currentJob': False, 'reviewDateTime': '2016-02-09 20:29:28.05', 'jobTitle': 'Employee', 'location': '', 'headline': 'Agree with the other reviewers', 'pros': '- Free lunch and snacks
- Free gym
- Internship pay is competitive. The pay is average if not slightly above market.
- Discounts on company games
- 35 hour work weeks until release time
- Lots of vacation days for full-timers
- Fun company events
- Good benefits for full-timers', 'cons': "Like others said, if you're under a good team, then I think you will really enjoy your time there. But for how small of a company, even the team to team experience can be quite different and some teams are very poorly run. 

- Management is juvenile and leadership is lacking. Because it grew so fast during a short period of time, I felt some managers that got promoted up are quite inexperienced and has no idea how to manage subordinates. 
- Cross team communication is non-existent. Leading to wasted time and effort. My team also lacked communication because my manager did not believe in meetings.
- Lack of career growth depending on your role. Never once had 1-on-1 time with my direct manager to discuss goals and expectations. No performance reviews of any type.
- Lack of opportunity to receive and give feedback. Hard to grow my career or improve the company when there is no way to give feedback. While no companies are ever perfect, the biggest red flag is that management never recognizes there is a problem.
- Interns are not used as potential for future hiring and might not be given interesting work to do. Don't expect any mentorship. As interns, we were told to not answer questions because it would bother full-timers. If you fail to execute a task, you would be treated as being incompetent. For these reasons, I would not recommend any interns to intern here. 
- Always sitting in the grey area of HR violations. (HR didn't do much while I was there) Be prepared that there might be borderline sexual comments directed at people.", 'overall': 2, 'overallNumeric': 2}
name: Demonware

{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-Vizeum-Global-Management-RVW22086551.htm', 'id': 22086551, 'currentJob': False, 'reviewDateTime': '2018-08-21 15:21:14.963', 'jobTitle': 'Media Planner', 'location': 'New York, NY', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'Media Planner', 'headline': 'Great People - Not so great politics', 'pros': 'I really enjoyed working at Vizeum
The people I worked with there are incredibly smart, caring, and have become lifelong friends outside of work.
The office in Tribeca is great and the amenities are wonderful (cold brew and beer on tap, espresso machines, accessible to many trains, close to Chinatown and Soho, many office events throughout the year, great holiday party, etc)', 'cons': "I was there during an interesting time when the company was semi-absorbed by 360i. The transition was very rough. There were a lot of promises about transitioning between accounts, opportunities to grow in roles, and a lot talk about valuing upwards growth (but it hardly ever happened).
There is a distinct divide between 360i employees and Vizeum employees even though we shared the same space.
It became clear that Vizeum was inferior: we were hardly ever acknowledged during company-wide meetings, there weren't a lot of opportunities to integrate work with other teams within 360i, and our upper management seemed more interested in their own integration into 360i rather than ensuring the vitality of existing Vizeum teams (a lot of higher level people transitioned to 360i accounts while leaving Vizeum accounts short-staffed for months to years, with the promise that we'll eventually find someone).", 'overall': 3, 'overallNumeric': 3}
name: Vizeum Global Management

featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-EY-RVW19357818.htm', 'id': 19357818, 'currentJob': False, 'reviewDateTime': '2018-02-21 12:04:47.107', 'jobTitle': 'Assurance Manager', 'location': 'San Jose, CA', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'Assurance Manager', 'headline': 'Manager in assurance', 'pros': '1. You will have a very hard time not falling in love with every single person you meet there.
2. Seriously, you will meet your soul mate(s) there.
3. Prestigious and looks great on the resume.
4. Your brain will grow a thousand times more powerful.
5. Forces you to conquer your fear of public speaking.
6. Fun team bonding and lifelong friends.
7. Stepping stone to high paying jobs.
8. Helps you work on perfecting your charm. You will learn from the most charming people how to really get people to like you.
9. HR really cares.
10. Big support network (IT, creative services, etc.).
11. Teaches you to be calm and in control.', 'cons': 'OK, I'm going to be discussing all the taboo things, and there are a lot of them. In spite of these cons, I still admit it's worth a five star rating. 
1. High performers are "designated" (you have very little control over your rating) by the partner group (can be a pro if you get selected. Seriously, I have worked with some of the supposed "fives" and they are not any different than my threes and fours.
2. Quality is extremely low. Sometimes I felt like I was working at McDonalds and not a professional services firm. The emphasis is on getting through work as fast as possible and expectations for quality are not realistic.
3. EY has a very hard time firing bad employees. If you get stuck with one it can be a nightmare.
4.  EY has a heavy emphasis on wasting time. For example, there are lots and lots of checklists which have no value that you have to  fill out. Also, they wasted money and time on creating "Canvas" which is literally slower and more awkward than the previous workspace tool, GAMX. There is a heavy emphasis on "reinventing the wheel" and fixing problems  that aren't broken with even worse solutions. Instead of wasting money on useless tools, that money could have been spent on your employees in the  form of compensation. Like I said, EY is really focused on attempting to look as though value is being created when in fact it is not. 
5. Lots of meetings. Appearances are very important.
6. Employees on global 360 accounts get better treatment.
7. Some employees (executives mostly) tend to overemphasize how important this work is. Let's face it, if it was really glorious work then we would have action figures. 
8. Looks are very important. Seriously, if you are a girl, you will get promoted based on how hot you are (the quality of your work is largely unimportant). If you are a guy, you are treated a little better but there is still a sexist undercurrent in the environment. This is advice you won't get from HR obviously, but that doesn't mean it isn't true.
8.  You will be forced to eat hours.
9. Your ethical compass will start to get weaker.
10. You will get a little cynical.
11. Lots of driving and travel.
12. "Family men" and married couples with children are more likely to be promoted. If you want to be a partner, you have to be married (few exceptions).
13. You will work on vacations.
14. Loss of relationships with family and friends.
15. Some backstabbing and credit-stealing (but not very common).
16. Comp is below market but that's to be expected.
17. Employee retention is not something management is interested in. This makes you replaceable and expendable (yes even as a manager, unless you have been "designated" as a high performer by the partner group).', 'overall': 5, 'overallNumeric': 5}
name: EY

Our enduring endeavor to take dreams seriously 

The passion of our students who will do what it takes to fan the spark of their professional desires into the radiant flames of realized career dreams

featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-EY-RVW19357818.htm', 'id': 19357818, 'currentJob': False, 'reviewDateTime': '2018-02-21 12:04:47.107', 'jobTitle': 'Assurance Manager', 'location': 'San Jose, CA', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'Assurance Manager', 'headline': 'Manager in assurance', 'pros': '1. You will have a very hard time not falling in love with every single person you meet there.
2. Seriously, you will meet your soul mate(s) there.
3. Prestigious and looks great on the resume.
4. Your brain will grow a thousand times more powerful.
5. Forces you to conquer your fear of public speaking.
6. Fun team bonding and lifelong friends.
7. Stepping stone to high paying jobs.
8. Helps you work on perfecting your charm. You will learn from the most charming people how to really get people to like you.
9. HR really cares.
10. Big support network (IT, creative services, etc.).
11. Teaches you to be calm and in control.', 'cons': 'OK, I'm going to be discussing all the taboo things, and there are a lot of them. In spite of these cons, I still admit it's worth a five star rating. 
1. High performers are "designated" (you have very little control over your rating) by the partner group (can be a pro if you get selected. Seriously, I have worked with some of the supposed "fives" and they are not any different than my threes and fours.
2. Quality is extremely low. Sometimes I felt like I was working at McDonalds and not a professional services firm. The emphasis is on getting through work as fast as possible and expectations for quality are not realistic.
3. EY has a very hard time firing bad employees. If you get stuck with one it can be a nightmare.
4.  EY has a heavy emphasis on wasting time. For example, there are lots and lots of checklists which have no value that you have to  fill out. Also, they wasted money and time on creating "Canvas" which is literally slower and more awkward than the previous workspace tool, GAMX. There is a heavy emphasis on "reinventing the wheel" and fixing problems  that aren't broken with even worse solutions. Instead of wasting money on useless tools, that money could have been spent on your employees in the  form of compensation. Like I said, EY is really focused on attempting to look as though value is being created when in fact it is not. 
5. Lots of meetings. Appearances are very important.
6. Employees on global 360 accounts get better treatment.
7. Some employees (executives mostly) tend to overemphasize how important this work is. Let's face it, if it was really glorious work then we would have action figures. 
8. Looks are very important. Seriously, if you are a girl, you will get promoted based on how hot you are (the quality of your work is largely unimportant). If you are a guy, you are treated a little better but there is still a sexist undercurrent in the environment. This is advice you won't get from HR obviously, but that doesn't mean it isn't true.
8.  You will be forced to eat hours.
9. Your ethical compass will start to get weaker.
10. You will get a little cynical.
11. Lots of driving and travel.
12. "Family men" and married couples with children are more likely to be promoted. If you want to be a partner, you have to be married (few exceptions).
13. You will work on vacations.
14. Loss of relationships with family and friends.
15. Some backstabbing and credit-stealing (but not very common).
16. Comp is below market but that's to be expected.
17. Employee retention is not something management is interested in. This makes you replaceable and expendable (yes even as a manager, unless you have been "designated" as a high performer by the partner group).', 'overall': 5, 'overallNumeric': 5}
name: EY

featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-The-Garland-Company-RVW30142607.htm', 'id': 30142607, 'currentJob': True, 'reviewDateTime': '2019-11-01 09:02:24.193', 'jobTitle': 'Finance', 'location': 'Cleveland, OH', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'Finance', 'headline': 'One of the Best Cleveland, OH Companies for a Reason', 'pros': '- Leadership runs this growing company like a small business. The executives know their employees and I feel as though they truly care.

- Merit based work environment - if you work hard and accomplish your goals, you will be rewarded and accepted by your peers.

- Fun work environment. Many corporate run events to keep things fun and create an atmosphere for you to get to know your co-workers.

- Employee Owned. This creates a healthy culture where everyone cares about doing their jobs well, because a job well done benefits all. The ESOP shares you get are gravy on top of your base salary.

- Free Healthcare for full time employees with a leading healthcare provider. No healthcare premiums here, only have to worry about co-payments and deductibles.

- Consistent and healthy growth creates new opportunities every day.

featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-Google-RVW4204034.htm', 'id': 4204034, 'currentJob': True, 'reviewDateTime': '2014-05-10 14:46:38.187', 'jobTitle': 'Software Engineer III', 'location': 'New York, NY', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'Software Engineer III', 'headline': 'Great balance between big-company security and fun, fast-moving projects', 'pros': '* If you're a software engineer, you're among the kings of the hill at Google. It's an engineer-driven company without a doubt (that *is* changing, but it's still very engineer-focused).
* The perks are amazing. Yes, free breakfast, lunch, an dinner every weekday. Aaaaaamazing holiday parties (at Waldorf Astoria, NY Public Library, MoMA, etc.); overnight ski trips to Vermont; overnight nature trips to the Poconos in the summer; summer picnics at Chelsea piers; and on and on and on. I don't see this going away unless the company starts hurting financially.
* Speaking of which, the company is doing quite well, which reflects in bonuses and equity grants.
* There a huge diversity of work ranging from defending independent journalism worldwide (Google Project Shield) to crisis response during disasters (see Maps during Hurricane Sandy or Tsunamis), to the best machine learning experts and projects in the world, to more mundane revenue-driving projects in advertising, there's really something for everybody.
* It's easy to move around within the company as long as you're in good standing (the vast majority of engineers are).
* The company is amazingly open: every week Larry Page and Sergey Brin host what's called TGIF where food, beer, wine, etc. is served, a new project is presented, and afterward there's an open forum to ask the executives anything you want. It's truly fair game to ask anything, no matter how controversial, and frequently the executives will be responsive.
* No, nobody cares if you use an iPhone, Facebook, shop with Amazon, stream using Spotify, or refuse to use Google+. The company is amazingly open and flexible.

Neither pro nor con, but general information on work-life balance, promotions, and advancement.
* Work life balance can be what you want it to be on most teams. (Some teams are in more competitive sectors and require more crazy hours all the time - but very few of them). If you do what's expected, you'll be fine at least for a handful of years. Working a roughly 40 hour work week is possible, and many people do it. There are also people who are hyper-motived and work like crazy just because they love it, or because they're competitive, or they want to get a promotion. If you work 40 hour weeks without putting in anything extra, you'll fall behind them as they advance and you stand still - and maybe that doesn't matter, so it works out for everybody. But at least know where you would realistically stand.
* If you excel and work your butt off, you'll be compensated and promoted. If you let yourself be a code monkey, and just sit coding with your head down all day, you'll be fine but won't advance. A big complaint from some Googlers is about not being able to advance "even at Google" with pure coding. Sure, if you're the uber genius who created MapReduce and Bigtable, you're going to advance like a rocket without having to do anything but coding; but if you're like most engineers at Google -- smarter than average, but just average compared to other Googlers -- you're just a good coder and not revolutionary. Code monkeys are important to actually get stuff done, and to be sure you absolutely need to be a good coder as a software engineer (it's the minimum requirement), but code monkeys won't advance because they're not leaders and they're easy to replace. To get promoted you need to lead and do more than just code. There are plenty of ways to lead other than being an official tech lead, so this isn't actually _that_ hard, so the real point is just that you can't just sit there coding what other people tell you to code all day and expect to advance.', 'cons': "* It *is* becoming larger, and with it comes growing pains: bureaucracy, slow to respond to market threats, bloated teams, cross-divisional tension (though nothing remotely approaching that of Microsoft's internal tension).
* The quality of the engineers is possibly dropping, but possibly not. It's hard to get real metrics, because as the absolute number of people grows, naturally the number of bad apples grows; as a percentage it's supposedly the same as it ever was, but with larger numbers of poorer quality engineers it just _feels_ like things might be changing for the worse.
* Also with growth means more internal-confidential data leaks (again, because of the raw numbers of people) -- product announcements being ruined, etc. That means the company has to be tighter-lipped internally to avoid leaks, which makes things less open. It's still an amazingly open place, but less so than it was even a couple years ago. The good thing is they recognize it and actively look to improve things because they know how important it is to keep the good culture.", 'overall': 5, 'overallNumeric': 5}
name: Google

featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-Grafton-Integrated-Health-Network-RVW30099141.htm', 'id': 30099141, 'currentJob': True, 'reviewDateTime': '2019-10-30 06:40:45.337', 'jobTitle': 'Anonymous', 'location': '', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'Anonymous', 'headline': 'Rewarding and tough work, folks with little resilience need not apply', 'pros': "Mission driven organization that is trying to do the right thing by their clients- that includes everyone from the direct care staff up to the CEO.  I've been with the company for over 15 years and could fill a book with heart warming stories.  If you work here, you have the chance to make a difference in the lives of others.  I mean a real difference.  From offering a safe space for clients who have suffered horrible tragedies to teaching them skills they can use in their daily lives to become independent.  Its beautiful.
Not only can you go to work feeling like you're contributing to a meaningful mission, but you can form life-long friendships with your coworkers who are with you through the good times and the bad.  After all, these are folks that form your supports- both emotionally and physically.  You will share deep emotional experiences at work that are hard to find in most other settings.
The organization is constantly looking at how to be a better employer.  Don't read the sour grapes on some of these reviews.  Annual bonuses and salary adjustments happen rather frequently- moreso than what you'll be finding in other nonprofits.  It also invests in its employees in the form of tuition reimbursement- which I've taken advantage of in getting my degree.  The minimum expectation? Get good grades to qualify for the reimbursement.
There are opportunities for advancement, with the tuition reimbursement opening doors, but also for travel and training.  All you have to do is show interest.
  The company even developed an alternative to restraint and seclusion, which was a game changer for me in my work.  I've seen it work, and its helped me or my clients get hurt like we used to back when we restrained constantly.", 'cons': 'Working in this field is tough.  I've been fortunate to see other agencies that work with similar populations and they all know this to be true.  When you're working with folks who have the behaviors we see (i.e. aggression, self harm, acting out), you are exposed to things that you typically don't see in other work settings.  Its what you sign up for.  From my experience, people are either cut out for this kind of work, or they're not.  You have to have a thick skin, and be ready for what will inevitably happen.  From the looks of some of these reviews, you can read it- where they've not stayed long and complain about how dangerous it is, or how the alternative strategies the company has developed isn't safe.  What a crock.  I've seen it work, in their toughest setting, at the residential treatment center, so I know it works.  But like anything, the staff member has to give it a chance.  I'd also bet the ones who complain about "using pillows" are the same folks who were constantly trying to control their clients through fear or intimidation.  If you're into that sort of thing, keep away.  Or if you’re here already- get lost.  The rest of us don't want you on board.  We’re here to help folks.', 'overall': 5, 'overallNumeric': 5}
name: Grafton Integrated Health Network

featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-Cloudera-RVW30016799.htm', 'id': 30016799, 'currentJob': True, 'reviewDateTime': '2019-10-25 07:20:14.36', 'jobTitle': 'Employee', 'location': 'Austin, TX', 'headline': 'For those who DO see the forest for the trees', 'pros': 'Bright Future - Cloudera is uniquely positioned to enable the world's largest enterprises to industrialize machine learning and artificial intelligence. We are enabling them to also break the shackles of public cloud providers by allowing them to switch between clouds when it is financially convenient for these enterprises. If you can understand the impact of these two pillars, you can understand to value Cloudera will drive in the long term.

Earning potential - Being in the Cloud space, Cloudera has to pay up, specially in essential functions: Engineering, Field Engineering, Sales.

Big enough, without the "big company" feel - Cloudera has around 3,000 employees, but has the potential to feel like a 1,000 employee company. This means you are still able to easily network and create your own career path with enough proactive effort

Confidence from top Investors - Carl Icahn believes we are undervalued. So much so that he has bought almost 20% of Cloudera stock. An agreement has been reached that for 2 board members from Icahn, he will maintain his current stake. This is the best of both worlds

New product release that is set to disrupt the market - time will tell the end story, but early signs show good promise', 'cons': 'Not for the faint of heart - The Enterprise AI/ML space is still developing, not anywhere near maturity yet. There is constant change, and one must be willing to buckle up, focus on the mission at hand, and expect the bumps of the ride.

Some processes are still being flushed out - Post merger with Hortonworks, the company doubled in size overnight. This inorganic sudden growth in company size meant that there was a delay in a lot of process implementation that a normal company would go through over time. 

If you're not one to take ownership, you won't make it - don't expect anything being handed on a silver platter. The promotions, the recognition, the "insert anything I believe I'm entitled to" will not simply come your way. Everyone has to prove their worth, build their brand, prove themselves, and earn it. If this doesn't jive with you, you won't jive with the culture.', 'overall': 5, 'overallNumeric': 5}
name: Cloudera

featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-HubSpot-RVW30390938.htm', 'id': 30390938, 'currentJob': True, 'reviewDateTime': '2019-11-15 00:31:47.343', 'jobTitle': 'Customer Success Manager', 'location': 'Cambridge, MA', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'Customer Success Manager', 'headline': 'Best place to grow', 'pros': 'The "Use Good Judgement" policy enables a fantastic work environment. It removes layers of bureaucracy that typically creates friction for employees. Want to go to Greece for a week? Okay just use good judgement. Want to work from a treehouse? Go for it as long as you use good judgement (aka get your work done).

Besides the great policies, HubSpot's best perk is the people. Diversity of experience is vital to self-improvement and HubSpot provides this through all of the incredible people you get to work with. Most HubSpotters have experienced something in their life that makes them "Shiny".  Our mystery dinners align us with people and an executive host that we usually wouldn't run into; after a few minutes you may learn that the colleague to your right had played professional baseball player and the women sitting in front of you was a detective in a past life. The growth you experience at HubSpot is gained through hard work (HubSpot is a challenging environment) and an openmind to other perspectives. Here's some other things that are cool:

1. Waffle Wednesday
2. Best nitro cold brew coffee ever
3. Silos of Cashews
4. Stock plan
5. Great health insurance; hubspot covers the vast majority of your deductible. 
6. Dogs at work
7. The gym
8. Awesome headphones (I can't go back)
9. Free tickets to science museum
10. Free tickets to museum of fine art
11. Free Kindle book of your choice every 2 weeks (UGJ)
12. Cereal buffet
13. Great selection of local beers
14. Nap room 
15. Meditation room (HubSpot can be challenging)
16. Peanut M&M's 
17. Awesome speakers for HubTalks and Fireside chats.
18. INBOUND(a week of Ted talks on steroids with trays of ðŸ¦ž rolls to end the night).
19. #Catspotting slack channel 
20. Making a quantifiable impact on our customers bottom line.
21. Helping the world automate tedious tasks (aka work smarter not harder).', 'cons': "If you think hubspot is the cure-all for your current work woes; you're gonna have a bad time. The cons of hubspot are the same as any job; there are highs, there are lows.", 'overall': 5, 'overallNumeric': 5}
name: HubSpot

featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-Ipswitch-RVW26543110.htm', 'id': 26543110, 'currentJob': True, 'reviewDateTime': '2019-06-08 07:45:17.563', 'jobTitle': 'Senior Network Engineer', 'location': 'Burlington, MA', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'Senior Network Engineer', 'headline': 'This is the place you dream about working for when you graduate from school', 'pros': "Ipswitch Corporate is situated in the ultimate location in Burlington, MA, where it overlooks route 95 and Cambridge st. It's connected to the building that Microsoft is in, which offers FREE access to their gym to all employed in these buildings. The views are spectacular - beautiful sunrises in the morning, clear view to Boston, and planes navigating to the Air Force Base. 

The culture at Ipswitch is unrivaled by the way they interact with each other. Caring, thoughtful, kind, inclusive, and energizing people certainly motivate you to go way above and beyond while doing your work. 

There is a generous benefits package that includes the best healthcare, dental, education, time off and bonus that I haven't seen in quite some time. They offer free drinks, snacks, and catered lunches  and get-together at various locations to help strengthen the collegial bond that really was the core of the culture. 

All levels of management were very approachable and attentive and would help you sort out any issues you were facing whether it was work or personal based. 

Every department has amazing team members who genuinely care for their work and their colleagues. I've never seen anyone sitting alone at lunch. This was a rock-star team of smart and creative individuals who met and exceeded their business and personal goals.", 'cons': 'They sold out to a public company called Progress Software.', 'overall': 5, 'overallNumeric': 5}
name: Ipswitch

featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-Maersk-Tankers-RVW28971718.htm', 'id': 28971718, 'currentJob': True, 'reviewDateTime': '2019-09-01 14:56:44.47', 'jobTitle': 'Third Engineer', 'location': 'Dallas, TX', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'Third Engineer', 'headline': 'Licensed Chief Engineer', 'pros': '1.Salary, Earnings & Money
 It offers a decent package right after you get out of college, which increases even further once you gain some experience and clear some competency exams. If you are doing good then you can be way ahead in your earnings in 5-6 years as compared to your fellow mates.

2.Financial Planning
 Almost every seafarer earns a NRI tag because of his job in international waters and earning in foreign currency (USD) which exempts them from income taxes. (Philippines policy). So, you can get your entire salary in your hand and plan your finances well.

3. Job Security
 Marine Engineering, requiring a specific training accommodates only the guys who have taken this course and prohibits competition form candidates of other streams.. This, less competition- More security.

4. Job Options & opportunities
 A well qualified and experienced Marine Engineer can switch his career on seas to other sites as well as he tends to possess a variation in his experiences. He can easily switch to management side of that company itself he was working for, earlier.

5. Varsatility in knowledge
 A Mar. Engg is expert in almost every thing which we come across in our daily lives. Form A.C. to pumps, from Refrigerator to fans. Everything. So, he can easily deal with household issues. 
 In fact, it is also said that "A Marine Engg is Jack of all traits but maybe master of few (or none)."
 ‌
 6. Family time 
 Yes, it's a bitter truth that a Mar. Engg. has to stay for longer durations when he is on job, but once he is back from sea, he can be all to his family. 24*7. Family time, tours, vacation. Everything can be planned without any problem.

7. Adventure.
 A Seaman gets to see the different parts of the world (ports very often). He leads a tough and challenging life onboard, which can only be experienced when you go on sea yourself.

8. Punctuality & Discipline.
 Job at sea requires uttermost level of discipline, patience and discipline which can easily be noticed in a Mariner.', 'cons': "1. Tough and Challenging Job profile
 Working on a ship and especially in its Engine room (as a Marine Engineer is a challenge in itself. The environment down there is not very pleasant and at times, it can burn the last calory of your body. Continuous and long work hours added with sleep deprivation is not a big issue if you suffer a major breakdown in Engine onboard.

2. Seasickness, Homesickness & Social Insecurity
 These are very common issues which arises when a fresher goes to sea for the very first time. Not adapting to the environment there, missing home and socially isolated (although there is internet nowadays on most oofthe ships) but still, seeing the the same 15-20 faces daily can ruin your Social life very well.

3. Away from family.
 A Mar. Engineer can't be with his family all the times. He needs or go away for his job and during this time, if he or his family needs each other, it turns out to be a real challenge to get together. Not always possible.

4. Continuous and regular study
 In order to do his job well, he needs to keep studying regularly and make himself aware of the development and modification in thier work areas. Additionally, it requires you to clear some promotional exams in order to get a pay-raise.

5. Health Issues
 Some people claim that, working on a certain type of ship (oil/chemical carriers) can lead to some heath issues later.

I hope, it gives you a fair idea of how is life of a Marine Engineer. Despite all it's challenges, it's an interesting field, No doubt.", 'overall': 5, 'overallNumeric': 5}
name: Maersk Tankers

featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-Manpower-Alberta-RVW29492473.htm', 'id': 29492473, 'currentJob': False, 'reviewDateTime': '2019-09-27 13:00:43.907', 'jobTitle': 'Recrutement', 'location': '', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'Recrutement', 'headline': 'Please dont do this to yourself', 'pros': 'There are no pros to working here', 'cons': "I cannot even begin to describe the amount of disgust I have for this company and the values they 'claim' to have.  It is an absolute disgrace.  I would love to say some good about Manpower, but it is very difficult.  The amount of BS that is in this environment is outrageous, from upper management right down to reception.  Nothing but condescending, rude, arrogant people.  
The recruiters are demeaning, management has no clue how to run their teams, and the programs, well let’s say I have received more helpful information watching Sesame Street.  
There is favoritism all over, you just must make sure you keep your recruiter happy or you will never receive work, keep your manager happy or they will find a way to get rid of you.  I remember how disgusted I was when I overheard one of the recruiters refer to a client who was going out on assignment as a ‘plug’ really that is the class that these people have?  
Not to mention the ‘clicks’ that exist in this office……mix this in with the gossip that everyone likes to spread (this including management) it is a toxic environment for anyone to be in.
They tell you how great the office culture is, how they are like a big family, how the turnover for office staff is low because of all this.  I beg to differ.  The office culture is similar to a grade 9 high school with all the clicks and he said she said bs on a daily.  They tell you how they like to invest in the current employees they have instead of seeking people from outside, again I call bull.  I will tell you how to get hired though, get in good with the CEO, even if you are less than qualified he can get you a position that you will be let go from in 2 months for having no clue what you are doing, long before they look at a qualified internal candidate.
I had the opportunity of working in this toxic environment for a very short time, and I tell you the best thing I got out of the short stay I had was my assignment back out for work.  
Upper management has no idea what is going on, they sit in their offices pretending everything is ok in the office when really it is falling apart.  The mid management gossips as much as the gossip between employees, they actually seem to be the start of it a lot of the time.  Laughing with the employees about past employees that have been let go, office badgering.  Honestly there is a lot of office bullying going on in this business, which is very unfortunate considering that they are there to help people not insult them.
Overall if there is one thing I could do in the end would be to warn anyone who is slightly considering working for Manpower either as a direct employee or as a temp, there are so many other choices out there with companies who would treat you more humanely, I mean it would be hard not too, keep your options open as this is NOT a healthy environment for any normal human being.  For those of you who choose to stay, may I suggest some time with a qualified psychologist?", 'overall': 1, 'overallNumeric': 1}
name: Manpower Alberta

{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-Frank-Recruitment-Group-RVW30512794.htm', 'id': 30512794, 'currentJob': True, 'reviewDateTime': '2019-11-21 16:59:59.34', 'jobTitle': 'Senior Vice President', 'location': 'Charlotte, NC', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'Senior Vice President', 'headline': 'Building a Brilliant Business in the Queen City', 'pros': "We have the incredible opportunity in Charlotte to work for a start-up backed by a global organization and global private equity firm. Not only are we opening the doors for young and experienced professionals to take their careers beyond their wildest dreams but we're creating a business and culture that can only be accomplished through great people.

FRG, no matter where you are puts you in the driver seat and provides the tools, training and mentorship to catapult your career and make incredible money along the way.

The business centralizes itself around accountability and puts training and development at the fore front of it's philosophy. 

Not only are we providing world class service by placing great people into great jobs, we're having a great time doing and celebrate success hard! A brief snapshot of those perks include:

- Lunch Clubs - monthly top achievers enjoy an afternoon at a five star restaurant and in some cases local trips!
- First Fridays - early leave on the first Friday of the month, followed by happy hour.
- Incentive Trips - this year alone we went to Jamaica and Japan. In years past we've been in Iceland, Spain and Italy just to name a few.
- 10 Deal Club - luxury gift item or a paid trip of choice", 'cons': 'What we do takes dedication, persistent and a student mentality. Unfortunately a career that hinges on those three elements is not for everyone. As all businesses do, we have and will make mistakes as but most importantly we use them as opportunities to learn and better our business.', 'overall': 5, 'overallNumeric': 5}

{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-Mccurrach-RVW12308705.htm', 'id': 12308705, 'currentJob': True, 'reviewDateTime': '2016-10-14 03:06:46.85', 'jobTitle': 'Territory Manager', 'location': 'Birmingham, AL', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'Territory Manager', 'headline': 'Territory Manager', 'pros': 'Good first step into Sales, depending on DSM depends whether your experience is good or bad.
The role in itself can be very demanding depending on the Brand owner you work for.
I enjoy the role and made some good friends both at TM level and senior.', 'cons': "very poor pay - 16 - 18K 
A car that is tracked 24/7 365 days a year, even at weekends, so if you let your partner drive be aware the car is still tracked and any offences you will be responsible for.
They have recently tightened it up, to a zero tolerance, so if you 31MPH in a 30MPH zone it will red flag to your line manager, your allowed 3 offences in a week before going on a disciplinary, so you spend much more time looking at the speedo than watching the road.

The MAP course is great but a conn, your expected to do the role of a DSM for 12-18months on a TM salary with a 10% responsibility payment, so you can end up managing people who have been with company longer and are on much higher salaries.
There is also no guarantee you will be signed off as a grade 2 at end of the 18months, I know DSM's who have been development for nearly 2 years.
This is dishonest and unfair as your expected to pull in the same results as a fully fledged DSM.

Also with the new process now every MAP candidate has to go for an interview whether they want it or not, I have had interviews for DSM roles where it is clear they already knew who they wanted but had to go through the HR process so I felt my time and prep was totally wasted.
There is now so many people on MAP the opportunities are so few.", 'overall': 3, 'overallNumeric': 3}
name: Mccurrach

They have recently tightened it up, to a zero tolerance, so if you 31MPH in a 30MPH zone it will red flag to your line manager, your allowed 3 offences in a week before going on a disciplinary, so you spend much more time looking at the speedo than watching the road.

The MAP course is great but a conn, your expected to do the role of a DSM for 12-18months on a TM salary with a 10% responsibility payment, so you can end up managing people who have been with company longer and are on much higher salaries.
There is also no guarantee you will be signed off as a grade 2 at end of the 18months, I know DSM's who have been development for nearly 2 years.
This is dishonest and unfair as your expected to pull in the same results as a fully fledged DSM.

Also with the new process now every MAP candidate has to go for an interview whether they want it or not, I have had interviews for DSM roles where it is clear they already knew who they wanted but had to go through the HR process so I felt my time and prep was totally wasted.
There is now so many people on MAP the opportunities are so few.", 'overall': 3, 'overallNumeric': 3}
name: Mccurrach

{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-McHale-and-Associates-RVW25933203.htm', 'id': 25933203, 'currentJob': False, 'reviewDateTime': '2019-05-01 08:59:49.97', 'jobTitle': 'Performance Engineer', 'location': 'Knoxville, TN', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'Performance Engineer', 'headline': 'Great Place For New Engineering Grads! You Will See The World.', 'pros': '- Great place for new engineering graduates!
- Decent base salary pay with paid overtime when working on a project in the field. Overtime is 1.5x, however the 0.5x comes at the end of the year as a sort of "bonus" if the company is doing well.  
- Very relaxed company culture. I.e. no dress code,  frequent coffee pot socializing,  etc.
- Travel all over the U.S.A. and the world! Travel is mostly domestic with around 2 international trips per year for a Performance Engineer 1, more international travel for more experienced engineers.  Average trip length is 2 weeks.
- Ability to keep all frequent flyer miles earned, hotel points, and rental car rewards! This is by far one of the biggest pros of working at this company. 
- Minimal HR presence in Knoxville office. (HR is located in Redmond, WA)
- Very intelligent group of people to work with, you will learn a lot from most everyone at the company.', 'cons': '- Poor work/life balance. This place is not for you if you are married or have family responsibilities.
- Approximately 40% travel during the year. This is great at first but the excitement fades quickly.
- Travel is often scheduled at the last minute. Makes it difficult to maintain relationships outside of work.
- Scheduled travel is commonly extended or delayed.  
- Non-existent formal training program for new hires. Makes the learning curve that much more steep for generating models, creating documents, and learning field techniques. 
- Non-existent feedback/annual reviews.', 'overall': 4, 'overallNumeric': 4}
