featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-MoGi-Group-RVW23429032.htm', 'id': 23429032, 'currentJob': False, 'reviewDateTime': '2018-11-15 07:57:02.037', 'jobTitle': 'Employee', 'location': '', 'headline': 'Do Not Work Here', 'pros': '- Industry: You took one very small, insignificant step into the game industry as a customer support agent answering tickets. Here’s the catch: That’s as good as it will get with MoGi Group.', 'cons': '- Insular Community: It’s all fun and games until you wind up in drama. There may be employees from all over the world working within the company but keep to yourself. The closer the family, the closer a dilemma. Coming witness to multiple scandals, you can look at someone funny and end up reported to HR. (See: Human Resources)

- Managers: I cannot think of a single nice thing to say about anyone in charge of the overall MoGi Group operations and that is truly pathetic. The management team are two-faced. This is particularly demonstrated when they promise a contract or raise but it’ll never happen. “If you find another job, take it.” What company ENCOURAGES their employees to find work elsewhere instead of fighting for them?

The management team will ask favors outside your job description and expect it for free. This is blatant abuse of power and takes full advantage of the staff. In addition and moreover, the team leads will push their workload onto you so they can play video games or watch a football match. Hilariously, this causes a huge scramble for information when the big bosses require a status report. A tip for those underpaid, pretend to know nothing and watch your managers panic. Remember that this is THEIR responsibility.

All while doing the above, they will try to sell this job as a learning experience. Do not take on more than this job is worth. You will not receive experience worthy to move up within the video game industry through this job and it is the equivalent of volunteer work, which will not impress an employer. Do not trust them.

- Wage Discrimination: Unless you are German or won the HR lottery, you will not receive a wage even close to the legal minimum. An intern receives a six-month contract for a rate of €500 a month with the CHANCE of receiving either an extended internship contract or a full-time employee contract. Be warned, the latter is incredibly rare and dangles in front of you on a string.

The internship program offered by the MoGi Group qualifies as a paid position. Therefore, interns are legally required to be paid the federal minimum wage. Start paying your employees and treating them with respect, MoGi Group.

- Human Resources: A key role to being a human resource specialist is to handle employee relations. Time and time again they have shown zero concern to someone employed under an internship or freelance position. If you are an intern trying to leave the job, HR will not provide the *REQUIRED* P45 form. Moreover, you can commit documented sexual harassment multiple times and still remain employed.

- Late Payment: While the MoGi Group headquarters is located within Park West, Ireland, pay stubs come from Athens, Greece - where human resources manages. As such, payments are commonly (and disgracefully) late. It is a legal right within Ireland to receive payment on time. To current employees who are not receiving their payment on time, I encourage you to place a formal complaint to the Workplace Relations Commission or seek additional information at your local Citizens Information Centre.

- Unsecured Data: As an ex-intern, I still have access to several confidential documents, meaning that my information was never removed from their systems. This raises not only a concern for the company as vital documents can be easily breached but current and past employees are subject to no data privacy as the MoGi Group is breaching the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR). While HR is required by law to retain records for at least six years, employee data is subject to the same protections as client and customer data.

Perhaps, MoGi Group, you will heed this review and take these complaints more seriously as your company can be fined at least 2% of annual global turnover. After all, any employee and intern should be familiar to your penny-pinching ways by now.', 'overall': 1, 'overallNumeric': 1}
name: MoGi Group

featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-Frank-Recruitment-Group-RVW30512794.htm', 'id': 30512794, 'currentJob': True, 'reviewDateTime': '2019-11-21 16:59:59.34', 'jobTitle': 'Senior Vice President', 'location': 'Charlotte, NC', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'Senior Vice President', 'headline': 'Building a Brilliant Business in the Queen City', 'pros': "We have the incredible opportunity in Charlotte to work for a start-up backed by a global organization and global private equity firm. Not only are we opening the doors for young and experienced professionals to take their careers beyond their wildest dreams but we're creating a business and culture that can only be accomplished through great people.

FRG, no matter where you are puts you in the driver seat and provides the tools, training and mentorship to catapult your career and make incredible money along the way.

The business centralizes itself around accountability and puts training and development at the fore front of it's philosophy. 

Not only are we providing world class service by placing great people into great jobs, we're having a great time doing and celebrate success hard! A brief snapshot of those perks include:

- Lunch Clubs - monthly top achievers enjoy an afternoon at a five star restaurant and in some cases local trips!
- First Fridays - early leave on the first Friday of the month, followed by happy hour.
- Incentive Trips - this year alone we went to Jamaica and Japan. In years past we've been in Iceland, Spain and Italy just to name a few.
- 10 Deal Club - luxury gift item or a paid trip of choice", 'cons': 'What we do takes dedication, persistent and a student mentality. Unfortunately a career that hinges on those three elements is not for everyone. It takes patience and positivity to build a platform for long-term success and in a world that promotes immediate results, that can be hard to cope with. 

As all businesses do, we have and will make mistakes as but most importantly we use them as opportunities to learn and better our business.', 'overall': 5, 'overallNumeric': 5}
name: Frank Recruitment Group

featuredReview: {'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-Oracle-RVW5218559.htm', 'id': 5218559, 'currentJob': False, 'reviewDateTime': '2014-10-21 16:15:55.177', 'jobTitle': 'Technical Analyst III (Support)', 'location': 'Denver, CO', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'Technical Analyst III (Support)', 'headline': 'Great benefits, good people, slow innovation, no raises', 'pros': "Every group/division can be different in how they treat their employees, but I'd say overall there is very good atmosphere of trust and fairness. There is a strong focus on education, and they reimburse for outside classes taken (Up to 5k/year I think). Benefits are good, and I'd say quite competitive in the market. Good 401K matching (they'll contribute a max of 3% of your 6% or greater). Free drinks in the breakroom. Flexibility to work from home at times. (If you live 50+ miles away from an office you can work full-time from home...policy).", 'cons': "They don't try to make the workplace anything special (maybe a pool table and arcade game are cliche or gimmicky?). In the 10 years I've worked there, they've given 2 measly %1 cost of living raises (this is the same with most everyone I've spoken to, some don't get any raises). You will not get a substantial raise ever, unless you leave then get rehired on (they will not match offers, better to leave). New employees that you train will make 10 - 20K more than you several years after you hire on (not just me, they do this to all tenured employees). They will give these untrained, less experienced people higher titles (again this is done to everyone not just me). You learn pretty quickly that you're dispensable. The company has billions in cash and they don't re-invest in their employees, just in acquiring new companies and hiring new people that know nothing that you get to train.", 'overall': 4, 'overallNumeric': 4}
name: Oracle

featuredReview: {'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-Oracle-RVW5218559.htm', 'id': 5218559, 'currentJob': False, 'reviewDateTime': '2014-10-21 16:15:55.177', 'jobTitle': 'Technical Analyst III (Support)', 'location': 'Denver, CO', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'Technical Analyst III (Support)', 'headline': 'Great benefits, good people, slow innovation, no raises', 'pros': "Every group/division can be different in how they treat their employees, but I'd say overall there is very good atmosphere of trust and fairness. There is a strong focus on education, and they reimburse for outside classes taken (Up to 5k/year I think). Benefits are good, and I'd say quite competitive in the market. Good 401K matching (they'll contribute a max of 3% of your 6% or greater). Free drinks in the breakroom. Flexibility to work from home at times. (If you live 50+ miles away from an office you can work full-time from home...policy).", 'cons': "They don't try to make the workplace anything special (maybe a pool table and arcade game are cliche or gimmicky?). In the 10 years I've worked there, they've given 2 measly %1 cost of living raises (this is the same with most everyone I've spoken to, some don't get any raises). You will not get a substantial raise ever, unless you leave then get rehired on (they will not match offers, better to leave). New employees that you train will make 10 - 20K more than you several years after you hire on (not just me, they do this to all tenured employees). They will give these untrained, less experienced people higher titles (again this is done to everyone not just me). You learn pretty quickly that you're dispensable. The company has billions in cash and they don't re-invest in their employees, just in acquiring new companies and hiring new people that know nothing that you get to train.", 'overall': 4, 'overallNumeric': 4}
name: Oracle

featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-Osborne-Wood-Products-RVW25682833.htm', 'id': 25682833, 'currentJob': True, 'reviewDateTime': '2019-04-15 07:51:25.713', 'jobTitle': 'Anonymous Employee', 'location': 'Toccoa, GA', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'Anonymous Employee', 'headline': "Like most jobs, only a bad place to work if you're lazy", 'pros': "I've been working for this company for ~5 months now, and my experience thus far has been pretty good. Starting pay for interns is great, work environment (at least in my office) can get slow sometimes but isn't stressful, and a lot of time and resources are invested into employee safety and procedures.

Pay - Starting pay for interns is at  ~$13/hour. 

Work Environment - I work in one of the back offices and I currently don't interact with most of the company, so I can't say this for everyone. BUT my work environment is pretty low-stress. Like I said, it can get slow, but that's with every job. The work I do is also moderately self-paced, which is something I value. Also, the office space is nice - if I need access to resources for my job, I can get to them.

Safety - The company really cares about employee safety, and this is something really important to me considering my former employer did NOT. The opening safety meeting is a little long and boring, but there are procedures & MSDS for just about everything on campus. Also, if you're unsure about any safety procedure, there is always someone you can ask.

Training - I was given written work instructions for my daily tasks to keep at my desk and my supervisor went over them with me.

Flexibility - Since I'm a student, I have an irregular work schedule most of the time. The company has been very accommodating with my work hours/personal days, so long as they are SCHEDULED IN ADVANCE. Policy for calling in late/sick is pretty reasonable - you're required to contact the office at least 10 minutes prior to the scheduled shift.
Also, at my last job, management would often forget that I had asked off for a day months in advance. That won't happen here - if you know you're going to miss work & you ask off in a timely fashion, those days will most likely be approved. Just be communicative and all will be fine :)

Opportunities - I recently asked my supervisor if I could branch out from my current position and add on another 'hat' in a different department. The response I received was timely and positive: management was very open and excited to have me working in between departments, and I was able to do so because the company is moderately small. My advice is if you want the opportunity to branch out, ASK ABOUT IT: no one will know unless you communicate about it.

Values - From what I've seen, the CEO & upper management really care about education; thus, work schedules are flexible around school schedules. Also, the company is really supportive of events & organizations in the Toccoa community - Osborne wants to help the community grow.

Employee Appreciation - Full-time employees have 24/7 access to the gym (it's a nice gym with pretty nice equipment and massage chairs). Also, I've received a total of 3 gifts in my 5 months here (one for Thanksgiving, one for Christmas & one was a handwritten thank you note.) Cake for birthdays & sometimes lunch.", 'cons': "** They really, REALLY care about punctuality, which isn't really a con if you can arrive a couple minutes early to clock in on time. (By on time, I mean that if you're scheduled to work at 8:00 and it's 8:01:01, you're late.) It is a little strict but fairly reasonable

Like I said before, my work environment can get really slow, but that's with any office job.

** Drug Testing - yes, they randomly drug test, but that's only a con if you do drugs. 

Some situations are handled on a case-by-case basis. Since the company is so small, some issues naturally come up that are unprecedented and thus have no policies regarding them. Communication is key in these types of scenarios.", 'overall': 4, 'overallNumeric': 4}
name: Osborne Wood Products

featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-International-Federation-of-Professional-and-Technical-Engineers-Local-21-RVW25418803.htm', 'id': 25418803, 'currentJob': False, 'reviewDateTime': '2019-03-29 15:27:16.177', 'jobTitle': 'Union Staff', 'location': 'San Francisco, CA', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'Union Staff', 'headline': "Can be a great place, but there's a lot of office politics", 'pros': "- The members are great; there are some that are anti-staff, but most of the members are appreciative of the work that you do.  If members are out of line and staff are put in a tight or hostile situation, management does usually have your back.  The members are also really smart people.

- You feel like you're really making a difference with the bargaining campaigns, and you make connections with great members

- Great office space; free beverages, and there's usually leftover lunch from union meetings

- Pretty good benefits; you get $1200 tech allowance every two years, paid vacation and sick time, and the staff union negotiates annual raises

- Pay is pretty good for union work

- You see the impact of your work 

- Some smart and capable coworkers. Some people have been in the movement for a while

- The union seems to be moving in a more progressive direction. We didn't use to have pickets or have rallies before, but now it feels like we have a much more fired-up base.

- There has always been favoritism at this workplace, but now it feels like your actual work product gets evaluated too. 

- Used to be primarily white male leadership, that's changing and the union leadership is starting to look more diverse.

- The new ED comes to social events with staff more often and has more progressive views. She also actually knows people's names.", 'cons': '- Lots of staff turnover. Under our new ED (she just started a year ago), 8 staff members have left; in a union with only around 30 staff, you start to feel it. We had a lot of staff turnover under the old ED as well, but it was announced when people were coming and going, so there was at least some transparency. Nowadays it just feels like people disappear.

- We have a staff union, but even with a pay scale, management arbitrarily puts people in higher or lower steps (this has happened under both new and old leadership). For example, someone with 8-10 years of experience in their field can be paid less than someone with less, or literally no experience, because management likes the person. And the person with more experience then sometimes has to train the favorite. 

- We have an internal staff union, which makes it harder for people to speak up. I've worked in places with both internal and actual unions in the workplace, and the internal ones are always more timid. Our staff contract is great, but it's common practice for employees to negotiate one-on-one side deals with the boss. Then it boils down to how much social capital you have to negotiate and if the boss likes you or not.

- There are also arbitrary perks given to new employees; i.e. some new hires get 4 weeks of vacation from the get-go, whereas employees who have been here for two or three years still don't have that much vacation. This type of weird individual benefit bargaining happened under both the new and old leadership.

- There was favoritism under the old ED; people would get slowly iced out and not advance in their careers, while other people would get conflated salaries. The same thing is happening with new leadership. Now it's just a different clique in power. It can get politically tricky if you don't know who you can trust or talk to. 

- Under our old ED, the union as an employer got sued for discrimination (i.e. women and POC getting passed up for promotions, while white people with less experience could get the jobs). Our union is getting more diverse, and our new ED is no longer an older white man, but the new ED's "in crowd" is still mostly white men, with few exceptions.

- The "in-crowd" makes all the decisions and has lots of meetings, and the rest of the staff get told about the plan without any of our input. Leaves a lot of scrambling and confusion about workflow.

- Disorganization and lots of last minute requests when a lot of things could have been planned out.  There are missing directives, and you'll get asked to meet lofty goals, but you won't have all the info or resources you need to do the work.

- INTENSE micromanagement by multiple people.  I feel like I don't have any ownership over my work. It's ridiculous the number of people I have to CC and get approval from, many of whom have no experience in my field. And they all don't talk to each other, so I get conflicting information. Or, I just get info at all and don't know what's going on. 

- There's a certain "yes-men" mentality, so you can't really be honest about your opinions. Also, it feels like staff's professional opinions are sometimes just completely disregarded when we do speak up.

- There's no room for career growth; it's a small org.

- Work-life balance can get really iffy. New ED comes from a union that grinds its staff, so I guess that culture kind of carried over.

- They sometimes put a vacation freeze in place. Some staff has had trouble getting their vacation approved months in advance, even with no freeze. Other have been asked to move vacations after they've already been approved, and booked flights and stay.', 'overall': 3, 'overallNumeric': 3}
name: International Federation of Professional and Technical Engineers Local 21

featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-PwC-RVW4963334.htm', 'id': 4963334, 'currentJob': True, 'reviewDateTime': '2014-09-13 11:54:31.77', 'jobTitle': 'Advisory Director', 'location': 'San Jose, CA', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'Advisory Director', 'headline': 'Great firm, but some changes on the horizon are terrible', 'pros': 'There is a lot about the firm that is great.  It is a great culture that values collaboration (below the partner level), that truly values diversity of its employees, and that is very collegial.  The Advisory business has grown significantly over the past 5 years since reconstituting a consulting arm with the acquisition of BearingPoint, followed by other large acquisitions of PRTM, Diamond and most recently Booz & Company (Strategy& - which is, actually, a dumb name for a company that garners eye rolls and open chuckling among the staff).  The firm has also made smaller tuck in acquisitions as well to fill in small, but important strategic capabilities such as Ants Eye View (for social marketing, social media strategy, and social listening), and BGT (for digital marketing agency work).

It is a place where you can build a great career if you can deliver great work, excel at networking across the firm, and can build partner support.  Exceptional employees are the "average" here, so if you aren't knocking it out of the park all the time then you can expect to only be rated in the middle of the pack, and receive nominal raises and performance bonuses.  

It has a strong brand in the market.  The firm's latest brand health index rated it at the top of the other "big 4" firms (Deloitte, KPMG, and EY) as well as other non-audit/tax firms like Accenture.  The Strategy& acquisition added significant strategy consulting capability to position PwC to compete with the likes of BCG, Bain & McKenzie (who have little to no post strategy execution capabilities...meaning they are good at telling you what to do, but aren't really able to stick around to help you do it).  

Bob Moritz (Senior Partner) and Miles Everson (Advisory Leader) are great leaders who do a good job at inspiring staff to provide great, differentiating client service.  They are personable, approachable, and genuine (if they are not, then they deserve an Oscar for their performances - oh, wait, we audit the Oscars...maybe a Tony then).  They have a strong vision for how we will shift the firm to a global operating model over the next few years (today, we are a collection of member firms with each territory representing its own firm structure) which will enable us to better serve our clients, most of which operate globally today.

All in all, it is a place that I am proud to work at.', 'cons': 'As noted by many, and as inferred by by comment around individual performance above, if you want to get ahead here you WILL work your rears off.  Late nights and weekends, with minimal complaining, are the norm for those who are successful.  The firm has tried to add in concepts of "flexibility" into our work force - but that is generally ignored in practice by those people actually delivering client work (great thought, poor execution).  

I know that many complain about what they see as the professional equivalent of "sweat shop rates" when it comes to compensation - but I honestly think that is over blown.  Sure everyone would love to make more money, but you can make 6 figures as a Senior Associate and almost $300K as a Director PLUS bonus...so, to me, the pay issue falls on deaf ears.  The one area that I think we could really improve on is in the area of our 401K matching percentage which is currently $0.25 on the dollar up to 6% of your contribution.  Many of our industry clients match dollar for dollar, so quarter for dollar is a bit of a slap in the face.  

The technology that we use as practioners, for the most part, is terrible with the exception of some of our new web enabled tools for pricing engagements and managing engagement economics.  For the last few years there have been many hints and encouragements that we would be replacing the much hated Lotus Notes (that's right boys and girls, we are still using the best of 1990s technology for email and calendaring).  There was a great deal of excitement and buzz in the firm - until we were told that we would not be moving to the standard...Microsoft Outlook.  Instead - we are "Going Google".  So, not only are we replacing one terrible system with another, we are not actually getting rid of Lotus Notes at all because 1) the Federal practice can't use gMail (the Feds won't certify the security of gMail's cloud) 2) certain accounts (like Microsoft) won't allow the use of Google products (Microsoft was so angry that they lost the replacement of Lotus Notes that we almost completely lost the account), and 3) the rest of the global firm won't be switching.  So we will be having to manage two separate email accounts and will be forced to use the terrible Google Docs over what everyone else in the world uses and likes - Microsoft Office.  Why did we select Google, one might ask.  The answer varies based on who you ask.  Some say it is because Google's cloud based tools will allow us to work in ways that we can't today for collaborating on the creation of documents and through Google's "Hang Outs"...this is ridiculous because Google's user experience is horrible (else, Microsoft would be losing market share to them in spades), and Microsoft already has the standard for collaboration through Link and Jive.  Some say it is because Google's cloud based services provide a lower total ownership cost - which is also ridiculous because Microsoft has Office 365 available through the cloud with Azure.  Some say it is because our technology isn't cool which is impacting our ability to attract talent on campus - which is the most ridiculous reason of all because who really joins a company because they can have a gMail account?  Also, I'm honestly not sure how we will be expected to use these fabulous tools in an offline capacity when we don't have internet connectivity (such as on a plane that is not equipped with WiFi).

The firm is also replacing its current performance management system (and process for handing out annual performance ratings and subsequent merit increases and performance bonuses) with a new system called the PwC Professional.  Basically, they are replacing a tried and true system of documenting written performance feedback (which is good for not only developing people but also for serving as a record of what people don't do well in the event an adverse action needs to be taken against an employee) with a mobile app that captures a rating against five dimensions and which replaces written feedback with oral feedback that has no memory and no record.  The "coach" who used to be responsible for representing their "coachees" at the Annual Review Committee time now has almost no role in the performance outcome of their staff displaced by the "relationship partner" who has responsibility now to personally know each and every staff member that they represent so that they can represent them to the other partner only "performance roundtable" discussions.  Partners today have very little time for junior staff, let alone demonstrated interest in their individual careers.  So now, a process that was cumbersome but was overly fair (you could only talk about things during ARC time that were documented - if it wasn't documented it was if it never happened and you had at least one person who knew you and advocated for you in the room when your performance was being discussed in the form of your Coach) and very transparent is being replaced with the equivalent of a papal conclave supported by a popularity contest.  Additionally, this mobile app (Performance Snapshots), only requires commentary if a staff member is not meeting expectations or is partially meeting expectations...so if you are meeting expectations you can't even comment on performance unless you are highlighting a performance differentiator that they only expect less than 50% of staff to have.  Lazy reviewers are incentivized through the design of the app to give everyone a meets expectations on all five dimensions and move on.  Our attrition rate has been very low for a professional services firm - it will be interesting to see what happens to attrition after the next round of annual reviews using the new PwC Professional.', 'overall': 4, 'overallNumeric': 4}
name: PwC

featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-Rakuten-Rewards-RVW30289863.htm', 'id': 30289863, 'currentJob': True, 'reviewDateTime': '2019-11-09 10:04:11.317', 'jobTitle': 'Android Engineer', 'location': 'Beloit, WI', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'Android Engineer', 'headline': 'Fantastic so far!', 'pros': "I just started a few weeks ago, but so far I'm loving the place. I'm at the Beloit office. I live a good distance away, so they let me work from home twice a week, which is very nice. 

But I actually don't mind driving the ~60 miles to the office most days, since it's pretty great to be there. Everyone there is super nice. And they have food - so much food!

When I'm in the office, I eat breakfast and lunch there, on the house. They cater lunches and post the next week's menu at the end of each week. And they basically have a fully-stocked kitchen. Tons and tons of snacks (dispensers with M&Ms and cashews all over the office). A full soda fountain with Coke and Pepsi products. And even a kegerator with a rotating batch of beer and hard cider. All just there for you to have whenever you want. All they ask is that you don't bring any of it home with you, which is totally reasonable.

As far as the work goes, most of my team is actually in California, so there's lots of video calls. I'm working on a large and complex piece of software now, but I came from a tiny dev shop before this, so the transition hasn't been without challenges for me. But the team has been super accommodating of that, and I really appreciate it.", 'cons': "Beloit isn't the best location to have an office; the Madison area would be far better. But much of their workforce at that office lives in Illinois, so it's totally understandable.

Can't think of much more than that for now, but I'm pretty new still. Will definitely update if things change in the future.", 'overall': 5, 'overallNumeric': 5}
name: Rakuten Rewards

featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-RECRUITERS-RVW7658244.htm', 'id': 7658244, 'currentJob': False, 'reviewDateTime': '2015-08-20 08:17:58.977', 'jobTitle': 'Recruitment Coordinator', 'location': 'New York, NY', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'Recruitment Coordinator', 'headline': 'Challenging initially - But very, very rewarding.', 'pros': "The Directors and management team in place at Recruiters are some of the most positive, supportive bosses I'll ever have. Their ability and motivation trickles down throughout the entire organisation making it both a rewarding and fun place to work for all of the staff.

The commission structure in place is fair and rewards hard work. They also have a strong emphasis on career progression and there's no red tape or bureaucracy when to comes to trialling new ideas or systems. If you have an idea or a method and it works, the Directors will 100% support it. 

There's an unbeatable social aspect in the business as well, very inclusive and broad from cinema nights to dinners on Baggot Street. Probably the only office environment I've worked in where everyone genuinely enjoys company events and there's no awkwardness whatsoever.Credit is due to the charismatic and friendly directors and staff that work there.

The company is growing constantly as well. Staff are encouraged to recommend people to join the organisation.

Recruiters is a sink or swim environment. If you work hard you will be rewarded exceptionally well financially and overall it's a fantastic, fun place to work. The only reason I left was for an opportunity oversees. I would highly recommend working here to anyone at any stage of their Recruitment career.", 'cons': "If you've never worked in a sales or consultancy environment before, the first few months can be very challenging. It's not for everyone.", 'overall': 5, 'overallNumeric': 5}
name: RECRUITERS

featuredReview: {'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-RES-Group-RVW13654643.htm', 'id': 13654643, 'currentJob': False, 'reviewDateTime': '2017-02-06 11:16:04.263', 'jobTitle': 'Employee', 'location': 'Needham, MA', 'headline': 'Interesting Projects, Very Poor Management', 'pros': 'The projects are very interesting, especially on the pharma side.  However, if pharmaceutical modeling interests you, you should look inside the industry itself.  The people here are smart and have built some lasting customer relationships.', 'cons': 'It is apparent from the other reviews that everyone experiences the same problems here. Mostly, the management environment is extremely poor and has been for a decade since the company expanded beyond 5 people.  Aside from many problems, the founders realize that they have very little management experience but refuse to do anything about it. It mostly manifests in the form of personal and career development, something that no one at the company cares  about. Knowledge is not passed on until it is absolutely necessary and no one goes to conferences or actively networks with professionals. The company environment is one of constant panic-mode project execution but with haphazard project planning and management.  The executives do not want to be managers, they want to execute projects and will never relinquish control over the details of projects that other people are executing.  They do not put forth clear expectations but internally expect that you will do projects exactly as they would, all the while not understanding why you cant do the project in the amount of time that they think they could. The compensation is well below par and benefits are almost non-existent. This is a consulting environment without the benefit of a consulting salary or strong leadership.', 'overall': 2, 'overallNumeric': 2}
name: RES Group

featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-Robert-Walters-RVW29768154.htm', 'id': 29768154, 'currentJob': False, 'reviewDateTime': '2019-10-12 08:31:06.95', 'jobTitle': 'Recruitment Consultant', 'location': 'San Francisco, CA', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'Recruitment Consultant', 'headline': 'Supportive team that hustles', 'pros': "It's a great office to get a start in recruiting especially if you haven't had prior experience.  Before joining RW SF, I was in a technical industry with no recruitment experience. They have a great team that coaches you through their process to be efficient and successful. 

I really enjoyed the opportunity to work with some of the fastest growing startups in the Bay Area. I was exposed to different industries, orgs, and leaderships that made me appreciate the value recruitment brings to these teams. This office is especially helpful to understand the SF market if you are a transplant and/or new to tech.

Some of my favorite things about Robert Walters:

- Great culture! They foster a collaborative culture where everyone is working together. People are always going out to events, HH, or just hanging out outside of work.

- They teach you resilience. Recruiting can be tough sometimes but the team here is able to coach you through the lows so that you can come out on top while celebrating the highs so that you continue to chase that feeling.

- The Robert Walters approach to recruitment is more strategic and high touch in comparison to other firms which is why the leadership here emphasizes quality over quantity. It really makes you take a step back to see the field as a chess board and how you can make the most out of each move.

-", 'cons': "- They are currently in process of testing new platforms, but, during my time, their platform is pretty outdated. Don't get me wrong though! It works and works well, but it just isnt as intuitive and user friendly as some of the other software today. 

- This is still an agency and a sales job at the end of the day. You only get out as much as you put it and it can be tough. You have to hustle and have grit when it comes to recruitment. This is not a startup where you can relax and get by. Although it is not KPI driven, there are other metrics of success which reflect your hustle.", 'overall': 5, 'overallNumeric': 5}
name: Robert Walters

featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-SLACK-Incorporated-RVW28672250.htm', 'id': 28672250, 'currentJob': True, 'reviewDateTime': '2019-08-16 11:27:08.39', 'jobTitle': 'Editor', 'location': '', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'Editor', 'headline': 'Forward thinking company', 'pros': 'I should preface this by saying that people’s opinions of their employer depend a lot on which department/which manager they answer to. It also depends a lot on that person’s personal temperament and whether they like their job in general, not just the company.
I love working for this company. I know my worth here. My colleagues all respect each other and there is a strong team environment. Everyone builds each other up.
There are plenty of things I like about my job, like the travel and opportunity to learn new things. It’s fun to work here. Leadership makes a concentrated effort to stay with the times, both for making it a nice place to work but also theyre not afraid to make changes to their structure and priorities to stay competitive. They shake things up.
The building is old but it never bothered me, and they do make improvements where they can. They have fun parties. Somebody bring in soft pretzels and have flex hours on Fridays.
I feel extremely comfortable here, like I can be myself and they want me here. I can grow here. I strongly recommend working here if you are given the opportunity.

featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-Turing-School-of-Software-and-Design-RVW28658820.htm', 'id': 28658820, 'currentJob': False, 'reviewDateTime': '2019-08-15 19:04:14.59', 'jobTitle': 'Fellow', 'location': 'Denver, CO', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'Fellow', 'headline': 'A great place to work', 'pros': '- Great people
  The people I worked with at Turing are some of the kind and thoughtful individuals I've come across.

- Great culture & mission
  Their mission is "to unlock human potential by training a diverse and inclusive student body to succeed in high-fulfillment technical careers." and it's literally written on the walls. Perhaps it's a non-profit thing but man the staff truly believes in this mission and considers it in everything they do.

- Rewarding work
  I got to teach people working to reinvent themselves and level up. It was great to see students grow and transform.

- Intellectually stimulating
  The staff at Turing pretty much continuously looking to improve the way they teach and interact with the students. In my three months there I went to at least six all staff meetings on improving process.

- Mentorship & growth
  I was an inexperienced instructor and they gave me the resources, connections, and time to grow my skill in this area. Things like 1:1 meetings, lesson evaluations, and a culture of curiosity were key.', 'cons': "- Teaching isn't software development
  The reason I don't work at Turing today is because teaching didn't scratch the same itch as software development, and that's something I personally need. Neither good nor bad, but know solving instructional problems has a different structure than designing a good API or class.
- Jeff Casimir can be a polarizing individual

featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-Stride-Health-RVW22082765.htm', 'id': 22082765, 'currentJob': True, 'reviewDateTime': '2018-08-21 11:54:18.737', 'jobTitle': 'Employee', 'location': '', 'headline': 'Hard and meaningful work on hard and meaningful problems', 'pros': "Every review mentions the people who work here with good reason: they are smart, kind, generous, and they care a lot. Enough cannot be said about the people. (I also think that the fact that people care a lot is a big reason for the degree of negativity in some of the unfavorable reviews. I'd encourage people to remember that work is just work, and things need not be so personal. While I'm on the subject so I don't let it bog down the rest of this review: some of the numbers/determiners used are, to put it politely, exaggerated.)

The marketing department is growing and maturing. I think lack of marketing muscle had been hurting us. If people are not aware of your product, no matter how useful it is, your reach will be limited. I've enjoyed seeing successes coming out of that team (and others, including carrier relations).

Strong recent hires: VP of Engineering, VP of People, VP of Customer Operations, senior product manager.

Worthwhile work! I think the market we serve is incredibly important. This is probably related to why the people here are admirable: it's largely a self-selected, mission-driven bunch. The company afforded everyone the opportunity to travel to various cities around the United States last open enrollment to assist rideshare drivers applying for health insurance by helping them estimate their income and navigate tricky enrollment questions. It was eye-opening and humbling. I have never had a single concern that our involvement in the gig economy has been predatory and exploitative. It's quite the opposite.", 'cons': "The market we're in is difficult. Brokering health insurance with Trump as President is dicey at best. This is why my title mentions hard work and hard problems. This is probably not a business that will ever print money. That's okay. We're trying to eke out a comfortable niche. 

The management team is fairly young, though recent experienced hires have altered that makeup. I think this con is the biggest reason for the unfavorable reviews, a consequence of how our company moving some focus away from health insurance to other areas conflicted with some people's motivations for working here, how the company could've/should've accommodated those circumstances, and communication difficulties throughout. But I also think that the company has learned from the experience. 

Our hiring standards sometimes seem too rigid for a company of our stature. This isn't a suggestion to lower the bar--the quality of the people here is listed as a pro--but when employees decide to move on to work at companies the likes of Google/Square/etc., it's worth considering if we need to change our current approach to recruiting, and how we can foster growth (and encourage retention) differently inside the company. 

Engineering resources for non-product team priorities are limited. It would be nice to give other teams (member experience and product operations) more support. We recently had a hackathon that freed up all team members to work on a project of their choosing, which resulted in a lot more cross-functional collaboration. Those instances should be more programmatically baked into the company roadmap/culture/etc.", 'overall': 4, 'overallNumeric': 4}
name: Stride Health

featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-Stripe-RVW30064108.htm', 'id': 30064108, 'currentJob': True, 'reviewDateTime': '2019-10-28 14:45:56.063', 'jobTitle': 'Employee', 'location': 'Seattle, WA', 'headline': 'Well intentioned company with great peers and growing pains', 'pros': 'I've been extremely impressed by Stripe since day 1 -- in how it composes itself facing difficult decisions, runs on the day-to-day, and goes above and beyond expectations on a consistent basis.

Leadership is inspirational (listen to a podcast with Patrick) yet very grounded when the going gets tough. Our company values ("operating principles") are lived by the leaders and it does really trickle down through the reporting chain. I seldom find myself disagreeing with decisions leadership makes, and they are quite transparent about their reasoning why.

Your peers are friendly, sometimes to a fault, and I don't notice much/any unhealthy competition in the engineering org. You can assume your peers are well-intentioned and are willing to hear you out fully, in the end doing what's best for the business (or, customer). A slight downside to this -- knowing the right people to talk to is an invaluable skill that isn't scaling so well as the company grows.

The mission of the company -- grow the GDP of the internet -- is arguably pure and apolitical. There is a sense we are building core infrastructure for the world. It's nice not to feel conflicted about your work.

I've been happy that our planning process is often long-term. You can successfully argue for ideas that might not result in immediate benefits, but will pay dividends in, say, a year. This applies to paying down tech debt to new products or features. Your argument has to be well articulated, though.

Finally, as a medium sized company, there is so much work to be done and opportunity for those who are willing to go out and grab it (even if it's not always obvious). Ambition and foresight are recognized and rewarded, even if you don't necessarily have seniority or tenure.', 'cons': 'Work-life balance can suffer depending on your ambition. Working a 9-5 is OK, but in practice a 9-6 is more common. (management generally seems to not care about hours worked, but actual productivity, which is a plus)

Internal tooling, testing, and development speed (especially outside the "happy path") has been a drain on productivity as the company has grown. It's invested in, but sometimes can be rough.

Stripe grew as a developers-first company, so some scaffolding and support from others orgs is missing. Engineers often have to take on extra responsibility that may seem tedious or unrelated at another company.

Growth / education / mentorship is well supported, but you sort of have to seek it out yourself.', 'overall': 5, 'overallNumeric': 5}
name: Stripe

featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-Synchro-Software-RVW18334304.htm', 'id': 18334304, 'currentJob': True, 'reviewDateTime': '2017-12-13 12:36:07.86', 'jobTitle': 'Employee', 'location': 'Berkeley, CA', 'headline': 'A Cool Team and Great Place to Work', 'pros': 'I started working for Synchro as an intern during the summer in the Berkeley, CA office for the Project Delivery Team and it was a great experience. As an intern I directly supported the Project Delivery Team in helping clients deliver projects with 4D for scheduling, construction management, and bid proposals; and create educational material for Synchro users. I enjoyed the work and company culture so much that I decided to continue working through the academic year. 

Through this experience I learned of the many pros of working for Synchro. One of my favorite things is working with such cool and skilled team that allows me to grow my skill set by giving the opportunity to work on different things each day. I can also say this about Synchro as a whole: you are always working with different clients on different projects in order to improve the construction industry with Synchro’s technologies. 

Another pro about Synchro is that is a global company, which has given me the opportunity to work on different projects from around the world, and also work with other team members of the project delivery team that are abroad. Although Synchro is global, it is also a small company, and I have met the entire Synchro Project Delivery (SPD) team during the annual SPD reunion. They are truly a great team to work with, which is motivated by their desire to improve construction. 

Something else that makes working for Synchro unique is that it is a software company, so I get to be among the first that see and work with new technologies like the HoloLens and the iPad, that are helping transform the way construction is done. 

The Berkeley office is also really cool. It is in the WeWork so there are always cool events during the week and you get to share spaces with other innovative companies.', 'cons': 'A con of working for Synchro could be that it is a small company, so you need to get adjusted to a small-company culture.', 'overall': 5, 'overallNumeric': 5}
name: Synchro Software

featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-Telnyx-RVW21430618.htm', 'id': 21430618, 'currentJob': True, 'reviewDateTime': '2018-07-11 08:29:06.987', 'jobTitle': 'Growth', 'location': 'Chicago, IL', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'Growth', 'headline': 'No such thing as "Sunday Scaries" here', 'pros': "Best team environment I have encountered thus far in my career! I wake up ready and excited everyday. This is the place where everyone takes an extra few minutes out of their day to ask how your day are (usually over the amazing breakfast spread our chefs have put together)

-Everyone is willing to go above and beyond - not because we have to but because we want to. Seriously this is THE BEST team environment I have worked in - can not say this enough.
-You create meaningful impact in your assigned role, and other roles you might help in (we all wear several hats and are happy to do so)
-If you want to learn and grow your skill set - Telnyx is 100% the atmosphere and company which allows you to do so. David and Ian are extremely motivated in allowing the team to try new avenues to excel in their vertical 
-Yes the hours are longer than a typical 9-5... but it doesn't feel that way. The environment is fast paced and dynamic so your day is never stagnant and dull. Usually 5/6 pm comes around (and you get the dinner notification from our chefs) and realize its been a few hours since you last noticed the time.  Bottom line, work here doesn't feel like work at all; it's interesting and future thinking.
-You will 100% grow here and the leadership makes it their personal goal to help your growth 
-Awesome swag designed from our marketing team
-Best food ever prepped by our awesome chefs (breakfast, lunch and dinner)
-Other company perks
-Team, team, team, team", 'cons': '-Most common traits of a start up - sometimes things need to be redone or changed after some time, but again everyone is happy to do so', 'overall': 5, 'overallNumeric': 5}
name: Telnyx

+IP Licensing Agreements to companies

featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-UnitedHealth-Group-RVW7573936.htm', 'id': 7573936, 'currentJob': True, 'reviewDateTime': '2015-08-13 14:25:59.473', 'jobTitle': 'IT Project Manager', 'location': 'Eden Prairie, MN', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'IT Project Manager', 'headline': 'Very heads-down', 'pros': 'I will preface this review with a statement you need to heed when reading this review as well as any reviews for this company -- "It depends on your area."  

This is a GIGANTIC company and YMMV depending on your group. Keep that in mind when reading.

Anyway, I've been here only 6 months, but I think I have enough of a feel for Optum to write a review.

The positives:
Great work/life balance: I never have to stay late, work on weekends, etc. I get 23 vacation days and my manager encourages me to use them AND completely unplug while away. 

Beautiful office: I work at the new Optum office in Eden Prairie. Building is modern and comfortable. Full size gym and locker room, and workout classes. Great parking ramp with a skyway so you never need to go outside in the rain or snow!

Work from home: VERY progressive with WFH! I can work from wherever I want. if I want to WFH one day, I can. If I want to WFH the whole week, I can do that, too. No one questions you.

Total autonomy

No drama: This is a very heads down place! I can't stress that enough. No one socializes with each other -- most of the time, you never even talk to your cube neighbors (because they're probably working from home). This is a positive for me though -- after working in some high drama offices, this is a refreshing change. 

All meetings are over webex: Great news if you hate in-person meetings like I do -- because there are very few! In the 6 months I've been here, I've had 4 in person meetings. This is also a con because you never meet your coworkers - read the con list for more info. 

30 minute "best practice" meeting times: You will not get invited to 2+ hour meetings, ever. Nearly all meetings are only 30 minutes. You might have the one-off meeting that's an hour, but it's rare. 

Good, standardized PM practices. But some of the documentation requirements are too rigid and can slow progress down. Our group is trying to move to 100% agile. Slowly.... All of my projects so far have been waterfall SDLC. Although as a new person, it would help to have a PM to shadow on some of these documentation/audit practices. I've had to learn as I go. 

- Great cafeteria with cheap prices. I can get a lunch here cheaper than I can bring it from home.

-Very engaging training classes!!! All training classes are over LearnSource (i.e. your computer) but the videos are well done and entertaining.', 'cons': '-Building seems empty because so many people WFH. It's almost kind of...sad. Such a nice building but no one is there.

-Internet explorer is the browser of choice. Yuck. You have to have special permissions to download Google Chrome or Firefox on your computer.

-If you like socializing with your coworkers, this is NOT a place for you! I can't stress that enough!! You will NOT meet your new BFF here. Everyone is very heads-down and focused on work -- no one chit chats about football or True Detective! You will not have coworkers stopping by your desk (to chat about a TV show OR to even chat about work). Most of my days, I don't talk to anyone in person. It's kind of depressing -- and I'm an introvert! There are no happy hours, social events outside of work, etc (this is a positive for me because I hate that stuff).

-Lots of contractors. Not that it's a bad thing - I've had great experiences with the PM contractors. They obviously don't last as long as the employees, and there's more contractor PMs than employee PMs.

-Difficult, as a new person, to know "who's who." There is no face-to-face meetings, so as a PM, it's tough to know who does what, since there's no face to put with the name. I struggle with this a lot, as I'm not used to this extreme of a "remote" workforce! 

-No wifi for your phone. Wifi is only available for visitors and you must have a user name and password. 

-Nearly all social media websites are blocked. Not really a con, but something you might want to know. You won't be browsing facebook at work!

-LOTS of meetings. Sure, the meetings aren't in person, they're over Webex, but you will have a LOT of them.

-Some "know-it-all" ego-driven coworkers, especially on the tech side. But this is typical of IT in general. I've witnessed this at every org in which I've worked.', 'overall': 4, 'overallNumeric': 4}
name: UnitedHealth Group

featuredReview: {'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-UPS-RVW5627014.htm', 'id': 5627014, 'currentJob': True, 'reviewDateTime': '2015-01-03 22:47:50.54', 'jobTitle': 'Delivery Driver', 'location': 'Auburn, ME', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'Delivery Driver', 'headline': 'Package driver for 27 years', 'pros': 'The pay is excellent .health care is 100 % paid with 100 %coverage...with exception to eye and dental which is about 70%..coverage...pension is outstanding..full package with wages and benefits is worth 130,000 yearly..without a college education I am grateful for the standard of living UPS HAS AFFORDED ME AND MY FAMILY!...and with 27 years of service I now get 6 weeks vacation with 8 sick days..and 9 paid holidays...we work hard like many people in the work force but we are well compensated!.', 'cons': 'The only con is while your children are young you give up a lot of family time..I never got to watch my kids play sports and missed a lot of their growing years...the job can be hard on your home life but if you can make it through those years you and your family will enjoy the financial freedom that UPS provides...and now I look forward to a prosperous retirement!...so hang in there all you young drivers...', 'overall': 5, 'overallNumeric': 5}

featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-USDM-Life-Sciences-RVW28836964.htm', 'id': 28836964, 'currentJob': False, 'reviewDateTime': '2019-08-25 16:25:28.97', 'jobTitle': 'Senior Computerized Systems Validation (CSV) Engineer', 'location': 'Dana Point, CA', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'Senior Computerized Systems Validation (CSV) Engineer', 'headline': 'USDM Life Sciences offers superior benefits for Professionals and Clients Alike.', 'pros': "I’ve worked for USDM Life Sciences for several years in various contracted roles, all principally involving Computerized Systems Validation (CSV) and Project Management (PM) of respective activities for many Life Sciences clients.  Most of these projects have required frequent or full-time, on-site presence, but I have also enjoyed considerable, rewarding project work that I performed largely remotely.  To accomplish this so consistently, I appreciated that USDM readily provided a great deal of genuine support and coordination with other USDM colleagues and expert peers.  

Personally, I've quite enjoyed the many opportunities to work with multiple client companies and project groups worldwide.  Although I was not seeking any particular career development opportunities, I believe that USDM provides a healthy and encouraging environment for professional development.  

In general, an internal PM is assigned for each project so that an expert can more readily focus on client needs without undue attention required for time- and budget-tracking or other contract or administrative duties.  This model also enables the client to interact with the PM as often as necessary to ensure effective communications and task deliveries.  Otherwise, USDM leverages and promotes expanding use of a wide range of technical capabilities enabled in large part by Microsoft Office 365, Salesforce applications and cloud communications, computing and storage technologies, both internally and for a growing base of clients.  

Although I did not often have sufficient opportunities to meet some of my USDM colleagues face to face, I’ve always felt part of a professional and sociable team that would consistently deliver best results for our many clients.  Now that I’ve accepted a new role with a different company, I still feel that I am part of the USDM family.  Indeed, I certainly expect to remain in touch and collaborate with USDM colleagues and friends.", 'cons': 'There really were no significantly negative aspects for me while working for USDM other than perhaps the potential uncertainties inherent in working under contract for variable periods of time for our clients.  That is, it is ultimately the client that dictates their changing needs to us as the provider of expert resources; and sometimes the client does not always understand what is best.  This sort of “downside” is really only an acknowledgement of the environment in which you agree to work as part of a consultant organization.  

Realistically, it is the client who must first propose or establish a reasonable budget and timeframe for work that we, as experts, can respond to and agree to deliver as much as possible.  If you are consulting, I am presuming that you already have significant expertise and experience that is really worth sharing.  USDM works hard to match experts with the job at hand and then to manage projects and communications very effectively so that reasonable tasks are accomplished and coordinated on time.  

As a consultant it is not always possible to be available for all potential clients, and it is likely that the more rewarding contracts will not be available at any given time.  In fact, there may be uncomfortably lengthy periods of downtime during which no suitable client contract is available.  Some other consulting firms often imply that sufficient work is always available to remain fully employed at all times; however, I did not expect USDM to always have my next assignment at the ready once the current one was completed.  

Everyone’s situation is of course different; in my case, I usually restricted myself to only local clients unless the bulk of any proposed work could be performed remotely.  Indeed, I enjoyed at least one interesting project where I traveled afar (out of the U.S.) only a few times while performing most of the work from home; but I would gladly work with USDM and that client again in the future, traveling as needed.', 'overall': 5, 'overallNumeric': 5}
name: USDM Life Sciences

featuredReview: {'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-VMware-RVW27577384.htm', 'id': 27577384, 'currentJob': False, 'reviewDateTime': '2019-06-24 13:28:33.1', 'jobTitle': 'Software Engineer', 'location': 'Palo Alto, CA', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'Software Engineer', 'headline': 'Great place to work that values quality of life and family', 'pros': 'VMware is a big company but in many ways had a startup vibe. That was great because the resources and infrastructure of a big company were there, but it gave most people I worked with freedom to work on many projects, influence, move around, and contribute in many ways. Plus, many things moved faster than they might at other companies of the same size. Perks were really great including bonuses, events on the campus, opportunities, etc.', 'cons': 'The biggest con is the annual layoff. During most of the years I was there, we were growing like crazy, beating expectations, gaining in stock price, etc. It was always positive and upward. However, every single January, it was known that there would be a round of layoffs, even when all numbers were looking great as they almost always were. Management called it restructuring. But, over the years, some really good people were let go for no apparent reason. Then to add insult to injury, a week or two later, there would be a company quarterly meeting discussing how VMware was doing so well and is still hiring, but they had to make some changes. It always felt dishonest and the sympathy for those let go came across as disingenuous.', 'overall': 5, 'overallNumeric': 5}
name: VMware

featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-Wachsman-RVW27973889.htm', 'id': 27973889, 'currentJob': True, 'reviewDateTime': '2019-07-13 08:37:29.133', 'jobTitle': 'Account Executive', 'location': 'New York, NY', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'Account Executive', 'headline': 'Enough is Enough: Context Matters.', 'pros': "I wasn’t going to post a review on here, but I just came across yet another two paragraph negative review from July of all times and enough is enough. While I am definitely bothered by a lot of things during my tenure at Wachsman, this Glassdoor section doesn’t tell the whole truth by a long shot, and the constant dunking (a lot of which is being done by the same people) is missing out on a lot of the positives, painting a very limited picture of the company to prospective employees. And there are significant positives, which is why many have stayed on (including myself). As negative reviews on this page have now outpaced the number of people who have left the company, read on. If you’re looking for a role at a startup, there is significant potential here despite a very rocky start, and you should have the full story. Here: good, the bad, and why context is king:


The GOOD:

Many of us, including those that remained after the tumultuous times (see the con section), are here for the same reason: there is very significant opportunity.

In the past month, Facebook announced a cryptocurrency and the President is talking about bitcoin. If it's not apparent yet, the crypto/blockchain space is the fastest growing industry in the world right now, full stop. It's basically 1999 in crypto, and while many projects are likely to fail, I’m entirely convinced the next Google, Amazon, or Apple of blockchain is already amongst the herd. Wachsman, despite its significant growing pains and thoroughly roasted Glassdoor page is still very much at the center of the growth. The firm is involved in some of the most important companies in the space, including several projects that are working with household names you definitely know. If you’re involved in crypto at all, you are always only a few degrees away from this company.

No matter your role or title, your responsibility at the firm enormous. For most PR people fresh out of college, a PR firm throws something like $33k at you and for the first few years of your career, you’ll effectively be a list monkey who help their bosses push electric scooters or new cell phones to consumer outlets by filling out spreadsheets. If you’re okay with that, because your primary objective is to work so you can enjoy the Big Apple while you’re young, you’re not necessarily wrong, but you’re also probably not going to have a good time at Wachsman, because your job will consist of much more and require rapid skill growth.

As a junior I worked long hours, and spent a great deal of time stressed - but I was paid very well and I never, not once, had a boring day. Because the industry is so fast moving, and the tech so complex (at least at first), its very much an all-hands, flat team experience. Following a grace period with a very in-depth training program, I was expected to learn how to brainstorm ideas, staff client calls, make pitches, draft written content, and more, all of which eventually culminated in content that was published in huge outlets. I got to learn more than I ever did in college about philosophy, economics, monetary theory, international commerce, politics, and more. I’ve met incredibly powerful, fascinating people in the industry, some of whom I can now, in some odd twist of fate, call friends. Notably, I want to point out that I never once felt like I was shilling some stupid product, as most pitches are largely around the tech undergirding really ideological developments that span across all sorts of industries and countries. I am confident that I would not have been able to have these experiences without years of mindless grunt work at any other firm, and based on the LinkedIn recruiters spamming my inbox, I think others realize it too. 

Overall, I’m optimistic about this firm and the industry, and while there's still much growth required, it offers very meaningful work if that's what you’re interested in. 


CHANGES (those made since CON section below):

Over the last few months, as most who have been in the space long enough could have predicted, the crypto market has seen a massive recovery. Likewise, the NY office has underseen a massive transformation and no, I’m not just using PR hyperbole - literally most of the original class of employees has left and a cohort of new employees have been brought on in their place. 

The cultural benefit is obvious here: as these employees didn’t go through the tumultuous headache last year, they are much more optimistic employees. While I greatly miss many of my friends, I’m definitely having a good time alongside this new class, and I have to say, it's made me more optimistic too. I used to feel like I couldn’t avoid drama no matter which direction I looked, but past beefs recently seem kind of pointless, especially because those supervisors are long gone and my new friends don’t even know the names of that terrible former boss that said x etc. It's actually kind of surreal to most current employees when they read the glassdoor, because the criticisms are largely levied at people who are no longer here. Very weird situation.

I think the most important development has been a change in leadership. A few months ago, we managed to poach one of Edelman’s big wigs as a managing director for the NYC office, a woman who ran their Middle East division. Over the last few months she has (with much fanfare from the rest of us) effectively edged out the remaining, inexperienced directors, who have since left the firm. In their place, a new round of directors have been brought on, and in addition to bringing with them more work experience, most of us have definitely noticed a more empathetic, kind leadership style. The next class of supervisors is also way more experienced. No more 20-somethings that were in the right place at the right time. One of the new ones even has a law degree. I only really wish this had all taken place 6 months ago, as it could have salvaged many good people we ended up losing.", 'cons': 'What went wrong before:

I’m writing this section to contextualize what happened before. As discussed above, many of the reviews are very at odds with the company in its current, and I think the historical context is very important here for explaining all the angry reviews:


During its first 8 months, in the midst of the greatest economic bubble in human history, a 1-man PR shop grew to 100+ people with 3 offices, having cornered as clients some of the largest projects (multi billion dollars) in the cryptocurrency industry while older PR firms, run by out of touch boomers, were still trying to figure out what the heck a bitcoin was. Despite great client work, during that period, and after, mistakes were made as it relates to employee management in the NYC office. 

Inexperienced OG’s in the company got rocketed up to director positions, and were incapable of handling the leadership responsibilities. The fast-paced growth and bad expectation-setting by leadership also gave several junior staffers promotion and salary expectations that were very out of pace with the rest of the PR industry. In order to keep up with unreal demand for the firm’s services, hiring standards were weakened. HR feckless, and struggled to punish bad senior leadership, meaning they were largely left to behave with impunity.

These problems were not super apparent in the first half of the company’s history because the perks were great. If you were a junior staffer, maybe your boss would be a hassle, but you’d be being paid sometimes 30% higher than industry average, you’d have a promotion in 6ish months, it was possible to work abroad in Dublin or Singapore, and there was a great after work party culture with cool venues, bottles, food, kegs, etc. Most importantly, you had real responsibilities with powerful clients (definitely not just making lists), that made your work purposeful.

However, starting in early 2018 and accelerating in November 2018, cryptocurrency markets experienced a bloodbath (the fourth in its now 10-year history), with several currencies dropping in value by 98%. Within the span of weeks (yes weeks), clients dropped like flies and reporters across all sorts of news outlets placed an informal moratorium on crypto coverage, feeling, obviously, as if they had egg on their faces from such in depth coverage of the supposed next technological revolution. Don’t believe me? Google “crypto layoffs”. From December 2018 through early spring of this year, crypto companies across the industry laid off tons of employees, sometimes 70-80% of the staff.


By comparison, at the bottom of the crypto market, Wachsman laid off around 16 junior staffers, about 14% of its employees. Having never conducted layoffs before, the leadership did it in a very abrupt way, leaving everyone quite upset- and rightfully so. For months after it happened, I would feel flashes of intense anger when thinking of my close friends who had been let go, never expecting to be jobless so soon after graduating college. Many of these employees’ perspectives can be viewed below. It is worth noting, however, that within 2-3 months, every fired employee had found a job, most with a pay bump or promotion.

In the spring that followed, in the absence of a booming crypto market, a damaged culture, and declining perks, the company’s previously underground cultural issues came to a head. Several remaining employees, fairly deciding that they did not want to rebuild the NYC office, left for greener pastures. 

Significant changes have been made since, see above. I want to reiterate that despite the history outlined above, the company in its current form has me very optimistic (and yes, even I am surprised I feel this way). The changes are very significant, and I would recommend not writing off the firm immediately.', 'overall': 4, 'overallNumeric': 4}
name: Wachsman

featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-Wayfair-RVW15033610.htm', 'id': 15033610, 'currentJob': False, 'reviewDateTime': '2017-05-12 09:29:32.137', 'jobTitle': 'Software Engineer', 'location': 'Boston, MA', 'jobTitleFromDb': 'Software Engineer', 'headline': 'A perfect place to keep your head down', 'pros': "Wayfair is a fantastic company if you're a software engineer who's looking to keep quiet, and not speak up when management treats you like garbage.  And it excels at finding leaders who are willing to go the extra mile to be untrustworthy and make you feel like your job isn't safe (and for real, it's not).", 'cons': 'Let's talk.

The company has been growing like crazy, and one thing that was never thought about was "can we actually hire at a sustainable rate, and scale accordingly?"  The answer was no on both counts.  Software engineers at Wayfair have a history of disappearing.  People who enter labs have an especially low success rate (70% make it through, and less than 50% last a whole year).  It's basically their way to run people through a burnout gauntlet, and see who survives.  And then you have the stories of the people who come in to work and are just asked to resign.  You'll see hints of it here on Glassdoor if you dig, and it's even worse than what you read.

They actually gathered all the engineers for a big meeting at the beginning of this year.  And they said that they were sorry that people felt scared and were sad that people felt like management didn't care.  Which is exactly how we felt.  They promised that their door was open, and they were going to work hard to set things right.  One person out of 500 stood up and asked a really cutting question.  AND THEN THEY FIRED HIM!  And there were 3 completely different official reasons given about it.  It's crazy.

The leaders also started up an engineering meeting to keep everyone on the same page and answer anonymous questions.  One time someone asked why we couldn't get snow days off, because it was tough to shovel for 3 to 4 hours and still work an 8 hour day.  So the leaders proceeded to talk down to us and reprimand us for even thinking about asking a question like this.

Turnover has been high over the past year, and the best people are leaving.  This worries management, but they still have no idea that the problem is actually them creating a terrible environment.

So if you're a good person who cares about the person next to you and leaving things better than you found them, don't bother applying here.  But if you're not, and you just want to keep your head down and not question anything, then this is the perfect place for you.  And if that's what you want, Wayfair gets 5 stars.  

Amazing career opportunities if you want to have the same job forever.  
Incredible senior management that value untrustworthiness.  
A fantastic culture of watching people next to you disappear.  

It's truly a perfect company.', 'overall': 5, 'overallNumeric': 5}
name: Wayfair

featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-X4-Group-RVW26314393.htm', 'id': 26314393, 'currentJob': False, 'reviewDateTime': '2019-05-25 05:02:13.4', 'jobTitle': 'Employee', 'location': 'New York, NY', 'headline': 'X4 Tech - NY Office *AVOID AT ALL COSTS*', 'pros': 'There are literally none whatsoever.', 'cons': 'PROFESSIONALLY:

- They micromanage every one of their employees to the point that their turnover rate is comparable to a fast food joint. All of the new hires come without experience and are trained in a very aggressive and backhanded sales approach (see: changing start dates on LinkedIn to say they've been with the company longer than they have). There is NO focus on what would be best for the candidate or client, all they care about is the check that they get every month. If their clients heard 1% of what they say about them after hanging up the phone these guys would be shamed in to bankruptcy.

- Gaslighting is the norm in this office; being told you can do it on your own and stop asking for help, attempting to do so and having trouble, then being told you should've asked for help the whole time is their favorite way to manage.

- Quantity over Quality in their KPI driven culture. If you're not on the phone for 80% of your time in the office, you're wrong. If you didn't send out 400 emails that day, you're wrong. No emphasis on building relationships with clients, everything is about your statistics and numbers. They'll fire you if you don't bill enough in your first quarter.

- Starting salary is low and non-negotiable, you're drawn in with the promise of incredibly high commissions and holiday bonuses but you realistically won't be seeing any high sums of money for at least 2 years. Pay is only once a month and commission checks could take even longer.
 
CULTURALLY:

- Misogyny is the way of life in this office.  Most conversation amongst management is about women's bodies, or sexual exploits. Any time a resume submitted by a woman is received the first comments are usually "She fit?"

- Instances of managers and trainees in openly romantic relationships has caused an environment of obvious favoritism and an unbalance of work load for those trainees.

- No work/life balance; They hire Brooklyn/Manhattan residents nearly exclusively so they can make sure you're in the office at the crack of dawn and stay until the sun goes down. If you're not in the office, you're fully expected to be working 24/7.', 'overall': 1, 'overallNumeric': 1}
name: X4 Group

featuredReview:
{'attributionURL': 'https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/Employee-Review-Keyword-Education-RVW22100159.htm', 'id': 22100159, 'currentJob': True, 'reviewDateTime': '2018-08-22 08:30:02.657', 'jobTitle': 'Employee', 'location': '', 'headline': 'Constant changes by unqualified upper management cause instability', 'pros': 'Good salary. Some centers have cool foreign and local staff who are fun and competent, but certainly not all. All centers are located on the metro.', 'cons': 'Illegal hiring practices meant Keyword recently fired half their foreign teachers with three days notice. A recent uptick in police raids on centers has led to deportation and imprisonment of foreign teachers. As of late many new hires have had their visas rejected after arrival in country without explanation from Keyword.

No career development. No upward mobility.

There is no strategic planning; ideas are simply rolled out without testing or consideration for possible issues that may arise. Roles within the Head Office aren't defined clearly, so important issues that arise are generally avoided or punted to someone else by management. 

The curricula development team does very little to support teachers, so be prepared to create lessons from scratch every time, something that isn't ideal for brand new teachers. 

The technology in the classrooms and teachers rooms is antiquated. Classrooms are small and dingy. 

Management recently told staff at one center that they want us to be "The McDonalds of ESL"...hardly inspiring.', 'overall': 2, 'overallNumeric': 2}
name: Keyword Education
